<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Strengthen Positions North of Kabul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
are strengthening their positions north of Kabul by forcing
thousands of non-Pashtoon residents to leave the strategic town of
Gulbahar, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few days, the Taliban, which are made up of
Pashtoons, have expelled about 50,000 people from districts around
Gulbahar, which is mainly inhabited by ethnic Tajik people,
according to aid agencies in the district.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic student militia seized Gulbahar and Jabul Seraj, 95
km and 77 km respectively north of the capital city of Kabul, from
the forces of ousted Afghan defense minister Ahmad Masood and
northern warlord Rashid Dostum last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Gulbahar, lying to the south of now snow-covered Hindu Kush
range, is the gate-way to the Panjsher valley, the stronghold of
Masood, who has dynamited the hillsides in the valley to block the
Taliban advance towards his bastion.
</P>
<P>
According to UN figures, tens of thousands people have left
their homes in Jabul Seraj, Gulbahar, Charikar and other areas the
Taliban militia captured this month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
