<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Bureau and Bank Co-establish Ticketing System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, January 26 (Xinhua) -- With a new computerized ticketing
system that goes on-line over the weekend, train tickets will be
available at all trading outlets of the China Construction Bank
(CCB) in this capital city of central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The system was set up jointly by the Wuhan Railway Sub-bureau
and the Bank's Wuhan branch. Tickets were previously sold in six
CCB outlets in the city.
</P>
<P>
More than 30,000 train tickets are sold each day in Wuhan, the
transport hub in central China, and the demand is even bigger
during Spring Festival peak season.
</P>
<P>
To accommodate the rising demand and improve the competitive
edge of railway transport, the Sub-bureau has increased its ticket
offices in the city to more than 60.
</P>
<P>
However, passengers still complain of long lines and other
difficulties in buying ticket during Spring Festival.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem, the Sub-bureau reached an agreement with
the Wuhan branch of the CCB at the end of last year to set up a
computer ticketing system connecting all the bank's trading
offices across the city.
</P>
<P>
This year, the Sub-bureau plans to establish another ticketing
system in the city, through working in cooperation with the Wuhan
Telecommunications Administration.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
