<HEADLINE> UK Insurance Companies to Demand Genetic Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- British insurance companies are
to demand genetic information, revealing a person'a likelihood of
developing certain kinds of disease, as a requirement for new
insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
All applicants for insurance who have previously undergone
genetic tests will be obliged to reveal the results and these
tests are designed to show the propensity to a range of hereditary
diseases, the Sunday Telegraph reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposals, to be published in a code of practice next
month, insurance firms could also deny life cover insurance to
those who refuse to release details to tests.
</P>
<P>
Critics argue that insurance companies could use the data to
charge punitive rates to those who appear to show an increased
risk and they fear the scheme will create an uninsurable
underclass because of their genetic make-up.
</P>
<P>
Medical experts say although genetic tests can reveal a
propensity to disease, these tests are still in their infancy and
are rarely to make a definite forecast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
