<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-26 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Time for Resuming Israeli-Syrian Talks: Levy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 26 (Xinhua) -- In the lastest of a
series of peace calls to Syria, Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy said today that now it is time to resume the peace
talks with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Levy made the remarks during talks with visiting Russian
deputy Foreign Minister Victor Porpvaliuk who is trying to
mediate between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Porpvaliuk said Russia was very interested in renewing the
Israeli-Syrian peace negotiations which have been suspended since
early last year. Russia has maintained good relations with
Damascus and may play a crucial role in getting the
Israeli-Syrian track moving again.
</P>
<P>
In another related development, Levy is expected to meet
late today with European Union (EU) peace envoy Miguel Angel
Moratinos to discuss ways of resuming Syrian talks.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos is to visit Damascus Monday in an attempt to
bridge the gap between the two sides over resuming the peace
process. Analysts here said that the EU envoy is now in a
better position than the leading mediator the United States in
mediating the Israeli-Syrian talks.
</P>
<P>
Syria was recently angered by the U.S. and Israel for
pressuring South Africa to defer a multi-million dollar deal
on selling advanced equipments to computerize Syrian tanks' fire
systems.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, former U.S. Secretary of State Warrent Christopher
also irritated Damascus by saying that the understanding reached
between Israel's previous Labor government and Syria did not
bind the current Likud government.
</P>
<P>
Under the understanding, Israel committed itself to totally
withdraw troops from the occupied Golan Heights in return for
Syria's sealing a peace pact with Israel. Syria is insisting
the talks be resumed on the basis of the understanding and
the "land-for-peace" principle.
</P>
<P>
The Likud government has refused to accept this informal
understanding and called on Syria to resume talks without
preconditions.
</P>
<P>
Following the recent Hebron redeployment, Israel has shifted
its attention to the Syrian track. Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu will travel to Washington in two weeks'
time to discuss the matter with U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
