<DOCNO> XIE19970127.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Government Determined to Confront Farmers' Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The Greek Government is
determined to confront the planned farmers' protest action, even
by resorting to force, a senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
"We may probably see riot police in the streets," Agriculture
Undersecretary Vasilis Geranidis warned.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking during a meeting of ruling party officials in
sectors of farming and cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
The Pan-thessaly farmers' coordinating committee announced
earlier that farmers would begin protest action on January 28,
gradually escalating until February 4 when they would resume the
road and rail blockades which caused widespread disruption
nationwide in December. The 25-day blockade cost the country 1.6
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The farmers suspended their action during the Christmas and New
Year holidays but vowed to repeat it if demands were not met.
</P>
<P>
These demands include lower fuel costs and lower value added
tax (VAT) on farm equipment, higher price supports, especially for
cotton, and a 1.3 billion U.S. dollar rescheduling of debts to the
state Agricultural Bank.
</P>
<P>
"Some have chosen the road to blind conflict," Geranidis said.
</P>
<P>
He added that "if they attempt to abolish every sense of a
constitutional state, causing such huge politic and economic cost
for the country, with dramatic consequences on the economy,
tourism, transport and exports, I do not think they leave much
choice to the government but to counterattack on the basis of a
constitutional state." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
