<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-26 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriots Protest Against British Military Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 26 (Xinhua) -- A group of Cypriots today
staged a protest against military exercises to be staged by
British troops in Akamas region at the western end of
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
More than one hundred people, some members of the House of
Representatives, environmentalists and local residents, gathered
and planted trees in the area, where British military exercises
are scheduled to begin Monday and last until the end of the month
on this Eastern Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
The protesters handed a petition to the Episkopi military
base, one of the two bases Britain has on the island since 1960,
asking for an end to exercises in Akamas in protection of its
natural environment.
</P>
<P>
International environmentalist organizations have proposed
that Akamas region should be turned into a national park.
</P>
<P>
President of the parliamentary committee for the environment,
Demetris Eliades and some other MPs addressed the protesters,
expressing their opposition to the performance of military
exercises in the region.
</P>
<P>
A number of environmentalists will tonight camp at the site
in preparations for Monday's direct action against British
military exercises.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the House plenum approved a resolution calling
on the government to intervene to stop the exercises. Deputies
also called for a ban on all future British army exercises
on the island.
</P>
<P>
The former colonial power, Britain, has retained two sovereign
military bases on the island under a treaty in 1960 when Cyprus
gained independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
