the U.N. agencies and the European Union over future
collaboration.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Aidid also suggested that he is ready to normalize the
relationship with what he called former enemy countries, but did
not specify.
</P>
<P>
Aidid's new political change toward the international
community followed separate meetings he held with the United
Nations resident representative Dominik Langenbacher and the
European Union's special envoy to Somalia Sigurd Illing this
week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Aidid called on the United Nations Security Council
to condemn the Ethiopian government for "carrying out deliberate
attacks into Somali territory defying the international laws."
</P>
