<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for Leniency from All Afghan Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani today called on all Afghan groups to show some
degree of leniency in their expectations in an effort for a
negotiated settlement of the Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president made the statement while meeting with
ousted Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabbani and Prime Minister
Golbudin Hekmatyar here today.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan leaders came to Tehran for the two-day Afghanistan
Peace Conference which ended here today with the endorsement of a
declaration calling for an immediate ceasefire in the war-torn
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The 62-year-old president said that the longer the war
continues in Afghanistan, the heavier would be the adverse
effects of the war with still graver disadvantages to the
future generations of that country.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is no military solution to the civil
war in Afghanistan, which warranted a sincere effort by all
parties involved in the conflict to agree on peace.
</P>
<P>
"The Afghan government is a sovereign government with
international legitimacy. So, there is no need for the Islamic
Republic of Iran to establish contacts with that government in
Afghanistan at venues unjustifiable by either side," he was
quoted by Iran's official news agency IRNA as saying.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani said that even the prominent figures among the
Taleban have noted that war would not be a proper solution to the
 present crisis in that country.
</P>
<P>
The Taleban, the main political and military player in
Afghanistan, refused to attend the peace conference sponsored by
Tehran since it enjoy obvious dominance and controls more
than 75 percent of the country.
</P>
<P>
The president said that Iran would continue to offer
humanitarian aid to the people of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani called on regional countries, especially Iran and
Pakistan, to act in harmony in order to bring about peace
and unity among the various Afghan groups.
</P>
<P>
Iran's state-run press today attacked Pakistan for military
support to the Taleban militia in Afghanistan while sending
low-level officials to Tehran for the peace conference.
</P>
<P>
With strong background of the Foreign Ministry, English daily
Tehran Times said that "Pakistan, the main patron of the Taleban
militia, sent a low-level delegation headed by its additional
foreign secretary to the gathering."
</P>
<P>
"It is also regrettable that Pakistan is still sticking to
its unrealistic approach to the Afghan crisis," the daily said
in an editorial.
</P>
<P>
Another English daily, Kayhan International, called the Taleban
"a creation of U.S., Pakistan and Saudi Arabia -- each of them
supporting the extremist group for their own reasons."
</P>
<P>
Persian daily Jumhuri Islami also published an editorial
criticizing Pakistan's move as "in collusion with the United
States over the Afghan issue."
</P>
<P>
Taleban militia seized the Afghan capital Kabul on September 27
1996, ousting the government of President Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
The fall of Kabul is considered as a major setback in Iran's
foreign policy. As a result, the relations between Iran and
Pakistan have remained cold since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
