<HEADLINE> Turkey Denounces Drug Charges from West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Foreign Ministry
today reacted strongly to allegations that Turkish government
officials had been involved in illegal drug operations.
</P>
<P>
A strongly-worded statement from the Foreign Ministry followed
today's reports that British and French officials had made the
charges against the Turkish government.
</P>
<P>
The statement complained: "It is noteworthy that such claims
lacking any documentary proof are made through the press and
certain institutions instead of being conveyed to the Turkish
government in the framework of the international cooperation
against narcotic smuggling."
</P>
<P>
The statement said that it is regrettable that some
European countries ignored Turkey's constant warnings that the
drug smuggling was a main source of income for the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
"Turkey is demanding to be shown with concrete evidence and is
rejecting all unfounded allegations lacking such a proof. The
airing of such generalized accusations against our country is
unacceptable," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The incriminating reports from Britain and France followed
allegations by German Judge Rolf Schwalbe in the Frankfurt
State Court that Turkish Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign
Minister was in personal contact with known Turkish drug
smuggling families.
</P>
<P>
British assistant home secretary Tom Sackville has said that
more than 80 percent of heroin seized in Britain originated
from Turkey and many narcotics operations had failed because of
Turkish leaks.
</P>
<P>
The Paris-based Geopolitical Narcotics Monitor has claimed that
drug smugglers enjoy protection by the highest authorities in
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish police seized 3 tonnes of heroin in 1996, accounting
for 22 percent of the world's total haul, and 7 tonnes of hashish
in the same year, according to official figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
