<HEADLINE> Turkey Makes Great Strides in Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has made more
progress in its privatization drive for the past week than it
did in the whole of last year, the Anatolia news agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Within the last week alone, privatization deals worth a total
of 320.5 million U.S. dollars were settled through the sale of
shares in Etibank, Anadolubank and Denizbank.
</P>
<P>
The sale prices of the three banks will reach 342.5
million U.S. dollars with accrued interest when payment by
instalments is completed.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Turkey's total revenue obtained in the
privatization process was 290.8 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned Etibank was divided into three banks --
Etibank, Anadolubank and Denizbank -- to facilitate the
privatization program, which was launched in 1995 and has remained
on the government's agenda ever since.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's financial market has been greatly encouraged by the
vigorous privatization drive. The combined Istanbul Stock Exchange
 Index reached a record high of 1503 points Friday, up 11.7
percent from Thursday's close.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Constitutional Court rejected a challenge by a
group of opposition deputies to halt the sell-off of the
state-owned telecommunications giant Telekom, removing a huge
block from the path of the government's privatization program.
</P>
<P>
Turkish sources said that the Turkish privatization process
started in 1984, but moved on slowly after President Turgut
Ozal died in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
