<HEADLINE> Measures Being Taken To Solve Water Shortage in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The government of
Tanzania is taking steps to solve water shortage in the capital
which has hit the city for the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
A press statement issued today by the Ministry of Water, said
that the measures, aimed at making available 25 gallons of water
to the citizens in the capital city daily, will cost 4.5 billiion
Tanzania Shillings (about 7.5 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Dar es Salaam has been experiencing a dry spell period due to
inadequent rainfalls which had caused the water source River Ruvu
run short of water.
</P>
<P>
According to the press statement, the city with about three
million people, needs 90 milliion gallons daily while only 60
million gallons of water can be supplied.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's efforts to increase water supply include the
construction of about 4,500 wells, drilling of 30
new bore wells which will be fitted with pumps. At the same
time, 8 exsiting boreholes are being cleaned to be fitted with
pumps.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a long term strategy for building a desalination
plant is also underway, according to the press statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
