<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-26 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Hopes US to Continue to Back Peace Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa expressed the hope today that U.S. President Bill
Clinton would continue to back the Middle East peace process
during his second term of presidency.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the remarks before concluding a two-day visit to
Saudi Arabia earlier today. He called on the U.S. to urge Israel
to comply with the recently signed Hebron deal, reports reaching
here from the Saudi capital Riyadh said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said newly appointed U.S. Secretary of State Madeline
Albright expressed to him her strong desire to continue her
country's role as the Middle East peace process co-sponsor. The
other co-sponsor of the peace march is Russia.
</P>
<P>
On ways of pushing forward the Middle East peace process after
the Hebron deal, Moussa said that "Israel has to comply with the
deal in a frank manner so the PLO-Israeli peace talks and
negotiations between the Israelis on one side, and the Lebanese
and the Syrians on the other side, would resume."
</P>
<P>
He said the deal, signed by Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat at the
Erez checkpoint between Israel and the Gaza Strip on January 15,
would help Israel regain its credibility in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt "refuses any Israeli proposals which violate the
spirits of peace and aim at amending the deals or finding new
formula in order to reach a peace in the Israeli way," Moussa
said.
</P>
<P>
The deal which was delayed for 10 months allows the
Palestinians self-rule in 80 percent of the West Bank town of
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
On Israeli accusation that Egypt derailed the signing of the
Hebron deal, Moussa said "Egypt doesn't care about the Israeli
accusations because it (Cairo) has its own politicians who draw
the major guidelines to push the peace process, that is why it did
not try to defend itself."
</P>
<P>
He highlighted the role of King Hussein of Jordan in ironing
out obstacles hindering the Hebron deal.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, who arrived in Saudi Arabia Saturday, delivered a
message from Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to Saudi King Fahd Ibn
Abdul-Aziz which dealt with the peace process, the latest
developments in Sudan and bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
