<HEADLINE> Philippines' Basic Industries Investments Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Investments in the Philippines'
basic industries dropped significantly by 75.62 percent to 1.27
billion U.S. dollars last year from 5.21 billion dollars recorded
in 1995, the country's investment department said today.
</P>
<P>
Latest records from the Board of Investments showed this sector
has approved a total of 52 new and expansion projects in the areas
of construction, textile, chemical and mining.
</P>
<P>
In terms of employment generation, the basic industries
absorbed 9,874 workforce, reflecting a 13 percent increase from
8,738 employment reported in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The mining industry contributed the biggest growth in
investments, registering a hefty 600 percent increase from 53.5
million dollars in 1995 to 373.3 million dollars last year.
Employment likewise surged by 546.12 percent to 6,948 from 1,272
jobs.
</P>
<P>
But the chemical subsector suffered most when investments
plunged to 5.53 million dollars from 3.79 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Although the construction industry garnered the highest
contribution of 885.6 million dollars, investments in the
subsector inched down by 34.4 percent from 1.35 billion dollars in
1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
