<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's main ruling party won
the last two seats of the lower house in the by-elections for five
vacant seats of the House of Representatives, the Election
Commission announced today.
</P>
<P>
Final results of the by-elections showed that candidates of the
Nepali Congress (NC) party had won in the two constituencies in
Baitadi and Rautahat respectively, the Commission said.
</P>
<P>
The by-elections were held Friday in the country's five
constituencies to elect MPs in order to fill the vacant seats in
the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Earlier over last weekend, the Election Commission had
announced that main opposition the Communist Party of Nepal
(United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML) secured three of the five
vacant house seats by winning the by-elections in the Kathmandu,
Sunsari and Rupandehi constituencies.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba's NC party, which leads the
three-party coalition government, earlier said it wanted to win
all the five house seats to replace the CPN-UML as the largest
party in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, the Communist opposition will remain to be the largest
force in the parliament with the three newly elected MPs.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML held 87 seats in the 205-seat lower house while the
NC part held 86 before the Friday by-elections.  
</P>
