<HEADLINE> Manila Reaches Regional Truce Agreement With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and
the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) today signed an
agreement ending their recent conflict in a southern Philippine
town.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which was forged after two-day talks in Sultan
Kudarat town in southern Maguindanao province, requires both
government troops and MILF fighters from making any provocative
actions in Bulton town, central Mindanao, in the future.
</P>
<P>
The six-point accord demands the dismantling of all the MILF
checkpoints in Buldon and the withdrawal of all the government
troops deployed in the town since January 1.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Maguindanao governor will help Buldon
mayor Makarampat Manalao return to his office, local police force
will continue to maintain peace and order in the area, concerned
government agencies will be sent in to assist in the relief and
rehabilitation of evacuees.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides still disagreed on whether they should
maintain their current positions in Buldon, which they controlled
after their two-day fierce clashes starting on January 16. The
unsettled issue will be discussed at the next meeting on February
9.
</P>
<P>
The clashes broke out after an ambush by MILF rebels against a
convoy of government soldiers escorting Manalao to take his
office. Manalao has been prevented from taking his office by the
MILF after winning the post in the 1995 local elections.
</P>
<P>
The two-day clashes left four government soldiers and 32 MILF
rebels killed and scores of others wounded. Although a temporary
ceasefire was declare on January 22, the two sides clashed again
on January 26, killing six MILF members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
