<HEADLINE> Iraqi Paper Criticizes Decision by UN Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 27 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi influential daily today
denounced a decision by the U.N. Sanctions Committee as "unjust
and non-objective."
</P>
<P>
An article carried in the ath-Thawra, organ of the Iraqi ruling
Arab Baa'th Socialist Party, strongly criticized the committee's
decision to block Iraq's import of badly needed consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
The committee turned down Iraqi requests to import consumer
goods like cotton yarns, pesticides, hospital linen, textiles and
pencils, etc., according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The paper said it is "unjust and non-objective" to block the
United Nations Development Program's (UNDP) request to carry out a
seed improvement project in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the UNDP worked out a project to improve
crop seeds for Iraq, but the sanctions committee blocked it under
the pretext that such goods may contribute to enhancing Iraqi
industry.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that after six years of sanctions, the
committee is "still making unfair decisions and acting in a manner
that has considerably harmed the Iraqi people and denied them the
simplest legitimate rights."
</P>
<P>
A preliminary report released last December by the Food and
Agricultural Organization said there is a drastic deterioration in
Iraqi agriculture, and lack of good seeds and other badly needed
materials have caused a sharp decline in grain production.
</P>
</TEXT>
