<HEADLINE> Albania to Use Army to Curb Violent Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian parliament has
decided to temporarily use a limited number of troops to curb
nationwide violent protests over collapsing pyramid investment
schemes.
</P>
<P>
Albania's national radio said today the troops will help police
guard government buildings, public facilities and roads. They will
act according to a decision made at an emergent session of the
parliament held Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The protests began about two weeks ago after the schemes, which
attracted investments by two-thirds of the 3.4 million population
in the Balkan country, went bankrupt. They had promised high
returns for small outlays.
</P>
<P>
The angry protesters, some of whom had lost their life savings
in the schemes, set fire to buildings and clashed with the riot
police. Nearly a 100 people were injured in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Aleksander Meksi promised Sunday on television
that the government would start paying back investors' savings in
the get-rich-quick schemes as from February 5. 
