<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Sino-French Joint Research Center Established </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The first Sino-French joint
research center has been established, its two investors, the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) and France's National Institute
for Computer Science and Control, announced today.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Guangzhao, President of CAS, said such cooperation can
promote mutual understanding among domestic and overseas
scientists, which is conducive to the development of sciences.
</P>
<P>
He added that the establishment of the joint research center
will make it convenient for the further cooperation among
scientists and manufacturers from both countries.
</P>
<P>
The Institute of Automation under the CAS in Beijing will
sponsor the new center, said an official with the institute.
</P>
<P>
He added that its research achievements will be mainly used in
China's high-tech projects and the country's other major projects
in the Ninth Five Year Plan (1996-2000), such as the set-up of
automatic control systems in newly-established factories and the
upgrading of the automatic systems in old factories.
</P>
<P>
The center will be jointly headed by Professor Ma Songde,
President of the Institute of Automation, and Olivier Monga, a
French scientist at the France's National Institute for Computer
Science and Control. The budget will be shared equally between the
two countries, according to the CAS.
</P>
<P>
The Institute of Automation, established in 1956, focuses
mainly on computer science and high-tech research and
development. It is the first in China to develop the controlling
technology in the satellite and space industry.
</P>
<P>
Its French partner, renowned for achievements in computer
science and automation, covers similar research fields.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Sciences and the French institute had a
cooperation agreement in as early as 1981, and two have since
frequently exchanged visits between scholars.
</P>
<P>
Zhou and Bernard Larrouturou, President of the French institute
signed the cooperation deal today in Beijing, in the presence of
Francois Fillon, France's minister of post, telecommunication and
space and Pierre Morel, the French Ambassador in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
