<HEADLINE> 4 Rebels Killed in Western Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Four members of Iran's anti-
government organization were killed by armed policemen in a
western border region, Iran's official news agency IRNA reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the four, who were from Iraq-based armed
opposition group People's Mojahedin of Iran (PMOI), were killed
in clashes with Iranian border guards and tribesmen.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the outlawed members were spotted
while trying to penetrate Iran for sabotage activities via
western border crossing of Mehran.
</P>
<P>
A local official was quoted as saying that four Kalashnikov
assault rifles, four anti-vehicle mines, some explosives belonging
to the Iraqi army, eight cyanide pills, some propaganda
pamphlets and photos of PMOI ring leaders were also seized.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the four-member team had been
dispatched to Iran for sabotage activities and intimidation of
people on the eve of the 10-day dawn celebrations marking
the triumph of the Islamic revolution beginning from February 1.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier report, two PMOI members were
killed and two others arrested in clashes with Iranian Law
Enforcement Forces in western province of Kermanshahan earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
Those who were arrested had confessed to cooperation and
coordination with the Iraqi intelligence agency for crossing the
border and their objective behind infiltrating into Iranian
territory.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, PMOI staged a series of bombings in the country during
the fourth parliamentary elections. Tehran reacted by staging an
air raid on PMOI base inside the Iraqi territory.
</P>
<P>
Mass'oud Rajavi, PMOI's leader, lived in Iraq at the
moment. There are about 20,000 anti-Iranian government troops in
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
