<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, January 27 (Xinhua) -- A warship that sank in the
Yangtze River during a Japanese bombing attack 59 years ago will
be raised from the water on Tuesday after 77 days of salvage work.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony will be held in the morning, and more than 400
reporters from all over the world will cover the event.
</P>
<P>
Part of the cruiser, named "Chungshan" after Dr. Sun Yat-sen,
the forerunner of China's democratic revolution, can be seen on
the water's surface at the salvage site of Jinkou.
</P>
<P>
According to an official in charge of the recovery, on Tuesday,
the warship will be lifted one meter higher than it was
today. Then it will be hauled to a shipyard 24 kilometers away for
repairs.
</P>
<P>
At 10:30 a.m., the Central China Television Station and the
Provincial TV Station of Hubei will present a live broadcast of
the process. 
