<HEADLINE> Syrian Vice-President Arrives in Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Vice-President
Abdul-Halim Khaddam arrived here today to continue his Gulf tour
aimed at reviewing bilateral relations and regional issues of
common concern, after ending a visit to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Khaddam, accompanied by Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
Al-Shara, was met upon arrival by Kuwaiti Crown Prince and Prime
Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Salem Al-Sabah and other
government officials.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day stay here, the Syrian vice-president is
expected to hold talks with the Kuwaiti prime minister.
</P>
<P>
This is the second leg of Khaddam's Gulf trip which will take
him to the other four countries of the six-member Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC), namely, the United Arab Emirates, Oman,
Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Official Syrian sources disclosed that the Syrian delegation
was seeking to discuss latest development of the Middle East
peace process in light of the Hebron agreement already signed
by the Palestinian National Authority and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The sources were quoted by the Saudi Press Agency (SPA)
as saying that the current tour was aimed at reviewing bilateral
relations, regional and international issues of mutual concern
between Syria and the GCC states.
</P>
<P>
Syrian sources here said Syria still insists on a
comprehensive peace based on the principle of land-for-peace
formula and in accordance with the international legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said the Syrian vice-president and foreign
minister, who arrived in Saudi Arabia Sunday, held talks with
Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz, Saudi Crown Prince and First Deputy Prime
Minister and Commander of the National Guards, during which they
reviewed bilateral relations and key developments on the Arab,
regional and international arenas.
</P>
<P>
Khaddam also conveyed a letter from Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad to Saudi King Fahd Bin Abdul-Aziz Sunday, which dealt
with Arab situation in general and the latest development of the
Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the Syrian leader' tour came amid a
flurry of meetings among Arab leaders in the Saudi capital of
Riyadh after the signing of the Palestinian-Israeli agreement on
Hebron earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein of Jordan visited Saudi Arabia Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa concluded a
two-day visit to the kingdom, during which he conveyed a letter
from President Hosni Mubarak to King Fahd about the Middle East
peace process, the latest developments in Sudan and bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, Egypt and Syria were the three major states
that launched the Arab summit in Cairo last year to coordinate
the Arab attitude toward Israel after the Israeli right-wing
government led by Binyamin Netanyahu came to power.
</P>
