<HEADLINE> EU Trade Balance With NAFTA Dipped in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
recorded a trade deficit of 2.9 billion ECUs (3.8 billion
U.S. dollars) with the North American Free Trade Area (NAFTA) in
1995.
</P>
<P>
The deficit followed two years of favorable balances in 1994
and 1993.
</P>
<P>
Despite the reversal, the ratio of the EU's exports over
imports with NAFTA, which includes the United States, Canada and
Mexico, has improved significantly since 1990. Then, the EU was
7.3 billion ECUs (about 9.5 billion dollars) in the red with
NAFTA, Eurostat (the EU's statistics body) said today.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat said trade between the EU and NAFTA was "extremely"
important, with about 20 percent of the EU's trade dealing with
the U.S., Canada and Mexico in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The EU had trade imbalances of 7.4 billion ECUs (about 9.6
billion dollars) and 5.5 billion ECUs (about 7.2 billion dollars)
with NAFTA respectively in 1994 and 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
