<HEADLINE> China to Carry on Anti-corruption in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China will step up the fight
against corruption in the new year, based on the nationwide
achievements made in 1996, a ranking Communist Party official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jianxing, secretary of the Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection of the Communist Party of China (CPC),
called for more supervision to be enforced among Party members,
and more supervision over Party members by the masses of people.
</P>
<P>
Hard work and thriftiness should be carried forward, and the
corrupt practice of spending public money lavishly must be
stopped, said Wei, also a member of the Political Bureau of the
CPC Central Committee, at the commission's eighth plenary session
which opened today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it is essential to build up an army of high-quality
and competent officials to oversee disciplinary inspection, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
According to Wei's report at the meeting, China has carried out
countrywide inspections of illegal activities concerning cars,
housing and abuse of public funds for personal use among some
Communist Party members and government officials. And officials
have been required to report their income and to turn in the gifts
they receive.
</P>
<P>
From January to November last year, a total of 116,000 people
were disciplined in accordance with reports from the masses, an
increase of 14.3 percent over the same period in 1995. And some
key cases have been solved.
</P>
<P>
However, Wei Jianxing pointed out that corruption remains a
serious problem, and some officials are not yet fully aware of the
importance of the anti-corruption campaign.  
</P>
</TEXT>
