<HEADLINE> Ukraine's Crime Rate Down in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Crime dropped in Ukraine in 1996
for the first time since the nation won its independence from the
former Soviet Union in 1991, Deputy Internal Affairs Minister
Leonid Borodych said today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the internal ministry showed the overall number
of crimes dropped by four percent in 1996, and crimes classified
as "serious" by seven percent.
</P>
<P>
But Borodych spoke with reserve about the ministry's
performance. "It's still too early to call the performance of the
police satisfactory," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that fewer than 30 percent of the 500 murders had been
solved. Police were still searching for answers in two of the past
year's high profile crimes: the attempted assassination of Prime
Minister Pavel Lazarenko in July, and the murder of politician and
businessman Evhen Scherban in Donetsk, in November.
</P>
<P>
"Scherban's murder would be solved," Borodych added. He refused
to comment on recent reports in the media linking Scherban's
murder with that of American businessman Paul Tatum in Moscow in
November.
</P>
<P>
Internal Affairs Minister Yuri Kravchenko raised concern last
December about increased crime in certain areas. The number of
kidnappings tripled last year, and organized crime groups doubled
in size.
</P>
<P>
"The number of economic crimes grew to 60,000 in 1996, for
which more than 68,000 people were tried, including more than
2,000 government officials," said Kravchenko.
</P>
<P>
He said the effectiveness of the police was limited by outdated
equipment and a general lack of funds, especially when dealing
with well-financed criminals with access to advanced weapons and
high-tech communication devices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
