<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Legislator: Reality Favors Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Tolbah al-Sanea, Arab member of
the Israeli Knesset (parliament), said that the political reality
of the Middle East peace process is going forward towards the
establishment of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
In an interview this morning with Voice of Arab radio, he said
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu' threats to occupy the
West Bank if the establishment of the Palestinian state is
announced were a mere attempt to win bargains with the Palestinian
Authority in their future negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"He is jockeying for concessions from the Palestinian side in
other directions," he added.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu seeks to keep this issue as a trump card in
negotiations with the aim of attaining political gain in return
for a recognition of the Palestinian state, Sanea told the
Cairo-based radio.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want to establish their own independent state
with East Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has reportedly vowed to reoccupy the West Bank, which
Israel captured during the 1967 Middle East War and is handing
over to the Palestinians through phased pullbacks, if a
Palestinian state is established.
</P>
<P>
According to the Israeli legislator, Netanyahu is keen to
activate the Syrian-Israeli track, underlining the need to create
a political reality in this connection, a matter that is related
to political future of the Israeli premier.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said he enjoys now enough support inside Israel to
conclude a peace agreement with the Palestinians by the year 2000
without resorting to holding a referendum in this respect.
</P>
<P>
According to the Oslo accords, final status talks, which will
be ended no later than May 1999, have to resolve such sensitive
issues as Jerusalem, refugees, borders and the Palestinian
statehood.
</P>
<P>
The PA now controls the Gaza Strip and seven West Bank cities
handed over by Israel under several agreements signed since
1993.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with British daily Times which was also carried
by the BBC this morning, Netanyahu pointed out that the recent
Israeli troop pullback from Hebron showed a possibility of
"achieving balance between the Palestinians' need to manage their
own affairs and Israel's need to protect its security and
interests."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli premier also expressed his hope for reaching peace
agreements with Syria and Lebanon, according to the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu refused to swap the Syrian Golan Heights for a peace
treaty and normalization of ties with Syria which insists on
restarting talks where they ended and on the basis of
land-for-peace principal and relevant U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
