<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Cross Plays Important Role in Disaster-Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Red Cross Society
has efficiently helped people all over the country survive the
earthquakes, fires, floods and other disasters in the past year,
an official with the society said today.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 million people in 27 provinces, autonomous
regions and cities in China were directly affected by natural
disasters in 1996, with over 100 billion yuan (about 12 billion Us
dollars) of economic loss, said Sun Baiqiu, vice-chairman of the
society.
</P>
<P>
The society has sent 17 groups of relief workers to
disaster-struck areas, including quake-hit Yunnan Province in the
southwest, and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region where
devastating fires broke out. Workers distributed the relief goods,
prevented the spread of epidemics and raised funds, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Red Cross is always set to cooperate with the
International Red Cross and Red Cross societies overseas, she said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, it collected 5.4 million Swiss francs of international
donations for 12 disaster-hit provinces and autonomous regions in
China.
</P>
<P>
It also helped the Hong Kong Red Cross to carry out an aid
project, involving 18.7 million yuan (about 2.3 million US
dollars), in the country, and received disaster-relief goods worth
24 million yuan (about 2.9 million US dollars) from the Taiwan Red
Cross Society, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
To prevent post-disaster epidemics, the society has sent 62,540
medical workers to the most heavily-affected areas. There they
have treated more than 3.8 million patients, disinfected drinking
water and sanitized the local environments, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
