<HEADLINE> Dhaka, Tribal Leaders Fail to Reach Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government and
the tribal leaders in Chittagong hill tracts (CHT) today failed to
reach an agreement, but both sides agreed to meet again on March
12.
</P>
<P>
Head of the government delegation Abdul Hasnat Abdullah, who is
also the leader of the National Committee on CHT, said that during
the last three days, "We held talks in a cordial and congenial
atmosphere. We had detailed discussion on issues raised by both
sides."
</P>
<P>
"We reached consensus on many issues. We will again meet on
March 12," said Abdullah, who just hold a three-day negotiation
with the leaders of the Parbatry Chattagram Jana Sanghati Samity
(PCJSS), political wing of the armed Buddhist rebels.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have been fighting a bush war since 1973 for
self-rule of three hill districts in southeast Bangladesh
bordering India and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for the government leaders and the
leaders of PCJSS to hold talks in Dhaka. This is also the third
meeting since the new government was installed following June 12
elections last year.
</P>
<P>
The last two meetings were held on December 21 and 24
separately in Chittagong hill district.  
</P>
</TEXT>
