<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Goals on Foreign Exchange Issue in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China's 1997 goals for the
country's administration of foreign exchange include the
implementation of a new law on import payments that goes
into effect on March 1.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Xiaochuan, Director of the State Administration of Foreign
Exchange (SAFE), said today at a national conference attended by
chiefs of provincial branches of SAFE, that on March 1, with the
adoption of the law known as the Provisional Regulations on
Supervision and Administration on Payments of Imports, SAFE will
be responsible for verification of payments for imports.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, verifications have been handled by designated
foreign exchange banks.
</P>
<P>
The new rule is aimed at establishing a supervisional mechanism
for the payments for imports under current accounts, Zhou said,
adding that this will ensure the authenticity of the payments and
the orderly implementation of the policy to make RMB yuan
convertible under current accounts.
</P>
<P>
The new law will standardize the payments for imports by
importers and the designated banks, and it will also prevent the
transfer of foreign exchange from the current accounts to capital
accounts, which may disturb the financial market, he said.
</P>
<P>
The regulations will be of great significance to the foreign
exchange administration after the adoption of the convertible RMB
yuan under current accounts, Zhou stressed, adding that it will
also have positive effects on China's foreign trade sector.
</P>
<P>
SAFE has made 1997 its year of administration and research on
the country's foreign exchange sector, Zhou noted.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, he said, China will start a comprehensive statistical
study of international incomes and payments, and strengthen the
analysis and forecasts of them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China will try to improve the utilization of foreign
funds, strengthen the regulation on the general supply and demand
of foreign exchange under capital accounts, gradually carry out
the long- and medium-term administration on outstanding foreign
loans, and support the reforms of large and medium-sized
state-owned enterprises, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the country will further improve its management and
administration on foreign exchange reserve, standardize and
develop the interbank foreign exchange market, and maintain the
stable operation of the foreign exchange market, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that China will continue its moderately-tight
financial and currency policies and that the domestic demands will
be under effective control.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that this year China will see an overall evening
out between imports and exports and a sound tendency in direct
foreign investment, as well as balanced international incomes and
payments with some surplus, and a basically stable exchange rate
of RMB yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
