<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Calls for More Public Housing Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The best path to follow for
China's urban housing reform lies in the establishment of a public
housing fund system and a consummate housing market, Vice-Premier
Zhu Rongji said.
</P>
<P>
At a recent national conference on housing reform, Zhu said
that the masses of people face the immediate need to improve their
living conditions, and housing funds have to be raised from the
state, businesses or institutions and individuals.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, housing is provided free of charge to individual
residents by government departments, state-owned enterprises or
social institutions. But the introduction of a market economy has
inevitably driven housing to the market.
</P>
<P>
The public housing fund system demands that individuals turn in
a certain portion of their income, their work units set aside
supportive funds, and at the same time the state gives financial
assistance.
</P>
<P>
In this way, steady and low-cost housing funds can be made
available, Zhu said. The practice in some places proves that the
method is effective in promoting the construction of more urban
housing.
</P>
<P>
He urged officials at various government levels to step up the
collection of housing funds and strengthen their management.
</P>
<P>
Through in-depth reforms and stricter macro-control over the
past three years, China's national economy has maintained a rapid
growth rate, and inflation has been curbed. It is high time to
speed up housing reform to provide low-priced houses to the
people, Zhu noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, marketable houses can help boost the growth of some
related industries, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He urged governments at all levels, urban construction units in
particular, to offer preferential policies concerning land use and
the collection of housing taxes and other fees. In addition, he
noted, profitable construction companies must also shoulder the
responsibility of building a certain proportion of low-priced
houses.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two years, China has launched a "comfortable
living program" in some cities by way of favorable banking loans
and related government policies, but the shortage of funds has
remained a problem.
</P>
<P>
In the future, the two methods will be combined, Zhu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
