<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Rural Economy Enjoys All-Round Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China's rural economy made
laudable progress in 1996, with both the grain output and the net
income of farmers hitting an all-time high, a national conference
on rural economy was told.
</P>
<P>
The total grain output exceeded 480 billion kilograms in 1996,
an increase of 13.5 billion kilograms from 1995.
</P>
<P>
The per capita net income of farmers rose to 1,900 yuan (229 US
dollars) last year, up eight percent from 1995, thanks to the
bigger harvest.
</P>
<P>
The output of sugar crops, tobacco and most of the other cash
crops has increased, while the output of cotton and oil-bearing
crops decreased due to the bad weather and less market demand.
</P>
<P>
The country's agriculture also saw steady growth in the animal
husbandry and aquatic products industries in 1996, with a total
meat output of 58 million tons, and 28 million tons of aquatic
products.
</P>
<P>
A total of 4.6 million hectares of newly-forested land
illustrates the development of China's forestry last year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese township enterprises are expected to turn out a total
of 7,600 billion yuan (507 billion US dollars) in 1996, up 19.6
percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
About 134 million people are involved in the flourishing
business run by township enterprises last year, an increase of 5.4
million as against the figure of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The project to aid the needy in rural areas has produced
good results. The average per capita income of farmers in 592 poor
areas around the country was estimated at nearly 1,000 yuan last
year, up 180 yuan over 1995.
</P>
<P>
Another seven million needy have been provided with enough food
and clothing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
