<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Offer Conditional Ceasefire to Opponents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
today offered a conditional ceasefire to its opponents, according
to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's acting Information Minister Amir Muttaqi was
quoted as saying they have only two conditions to a ceasefire:
First it wants exchange of prisoners of war and second it wants
the opposition alliance to bow to the will of the Taliban rule.
</P>
<P>
Muttaqi said the opposition must not use any truce to
strengthen its military position.
</P>
<P>
The ceasefire offer came after the conclusion of intra Afghan
dialogues between the anti-Taliban alliance in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic student militia, who now control more than two
thirds of the Afghan territory, boycotted the Tehran meeting on
the grounds that Iran was not a neutral body.
</P>
<P>
The Tehran parley asked an immediate ceasefire only if the
Taliban agreed to share power with the anti-Taliban alliance
including former Afghan military chief Ahmad Masood and northern
warlord Roshid Dostum.
</P>
<P>
"There will be peace in Afghanistan only if they accept the
Taliban," said Muttaqi.
</P>
<P>
Muttaqi made it clear that the Taliban, which imposes a strict
version of Islam, were not ready to share power with any hostile
factions.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban have inflicted major defeats on the joint forces of
Masood and Dostum during last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The student militia said it had pushed towards the Panjsher
valley, stronghold of Masood, asked the civilians to leave
Gulbahar, about 100 kilometers north of Kabul and gate way to the
Panjsher valley.  
</P>
</TEXT>
