<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Defends Rapidly-Growing Foreign Exchange Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- It's a correct policy choice
for China's central bank to purchase surplus hard currencies to
stabilize the exchange rate of the Renminbi yuan, a senior
financial official said today.
</P>
<P>
"It may not be the only correct policy combination to actively
attract foreign capital, stabilize the exchange rate and increase
hard currency reserves," conceded Zhou Xiaochuan, director of the
State Administration of Foreign Exchange.
</P>
<P>
"But right now it's a correct policy for China, in view of a
sustained and robust capital influx," Zhou told a national meeting
attended by heads of grassroots foreign exchange administrations.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China, the central bank, has been buying
surplus foreign exchange from the market since China overhauled
its foreign exchange system in 1994, to stop the yuan from
appreciating too much.
</P>
<P>
The policy maneuver has resulted in a rapidly-growing foreign
exchange reserve, which reached 105 billion US dollars by the end
of last year, up from 21.2 billion US dollars at the end of 1993
and 73.56 billion US dollars at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Zhou acknowledged that an opportunity cost exists for China to
hold such a large foreign exchange reserve.
</P>
<P>
"But such a large amount of hard currency reserve has greatly
lifted China's overall national strength and its viability for
international payments," Zhou noted.
</P>
<P>
It has also created a solid base for China to deepen reforms
and open wider to the rest of the world, and bolstered public
confidence in the Chinese economy, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
"These invisible benefits far outweigh the measurable and
visible costs," he added.
</P>
<P>
He urged foreign exchange administration agents to improve
foreign exchange operations and be more aware of exchange risks.
</P>
<P>
"You should study the international market more earnestly and
closely follow the changes in foreign exchange supply and demand,
in order to be able to readjust the currency, asset and maturity
structure of our country's foreign exchange reserves at a proper
time," Zhou told the meeting participants.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, the central bank governor, claimed that China
successfully handled the relationship between an increase in hard
currency reserves and the effort to curb money supply and
inflation.
</P>
<P>
Despite an increase of more than 30 billion US dollars in
China's foreign exchange last year, the central bank's discount
loans to the four state-owned commercial banks dropped by 60
billion yuan, he said, adding that the 6.1 percent growth rate of
the retail price index was well below last year's target of 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the term structure of China's foreign exchange
reserves was reasonable and the return on the hard currencies was
fairly good, Dai noted.
</P>
<P>
The country's four state-owned commercial banks are the
Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, the Agricultural Bank of
China, the Bank of China, and the China Construction Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
