<HEADLINE> General Elections Begin in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Moscow, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The polling in presidential and
parliamentary elections began on Monday morning in Chechnya, the
local republic which is trying to break away from the Russian
Federation.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Chechens queued to cast their votes as 435 polling
stations across the republic opened at seven a.m. Moscow time.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen candidates were running for the presidency while 766
contenders were vying for 63 seats in the Chechen parliament.
</P>
<P>
According to the republic's Central Electoral Commission, about
500,000 voters were registered in the 63 electoral districts prior
to pollings.
</P>
<P>
The polling process was being monitored by 72 international
observers from the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe, as well as by independent experts representing various
socio-political organizations.
</P>
<P>
The voting was to continue in Chechnya today until 20:00,
Moscow time, and the preliminary results of the count will be
known tomorrow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
