<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Achievements In China's Desert Control Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU January 27 (Xinhua) -- China has achieved successes in
its drive to control the spread of the country's extensive deserts.
</P>
<P>
It has staged 12 training courses for foreign countries and
trained more than 150 foreign experts in desert control.
</P>
<P>
One-sixth of China's landmass is covered by deserts, widely
located in the country's northern, northwestern, and part of the
northeastern regions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government attaches much importance to desert
control efforts, bringing the ecological project in line with the
state economic and social development plan.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Sciences conducted three comprehensive
surveys on deserts areas in 1950s, which laid a solid foundation
for working out an anti-desertification plan.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of survey results, Chinese researchers set up 16
research and demonstration zones in different biological and
climatic regions, finding out various ways to control desert
spread and a researching anti-desertification technologies.
</P>
<P>
The researchers have worked out an anti-desertification system
for a section of railway line, which links China's north region
with its northwest region and runs across a large moving desert
area of the Tengger Desert. The system has fixed the moving desert
effectively and promoted the transformation of sand into land.
</P>
<P>
A 400-km highway has also been constructed in the Taklimakan
Desert, the world's second largest desert.
</P>
<P>
The anti-desertification system has ensured the smooth traffic
of the highway.
</P>
<P>
Progress has also been made in improving the environment of
desert areas. A green belt covering an area of more than 40 square
kilometers has been established in Linzhe County in the southern
end of the Badain Jaran Desert, which has enhanced the local grain
production to 15 tons per hectare, and the research results have
been widely applied in the Hexi Corridor areas.
</P>
<P>
China's advanced technologies have made the development of
desert resources feasible. Using underground water in irrigation,
the researchers have produced thousands of kilograms of vegetables
in the hinterland of the Taklimakan Desert, and with plastic film
for covering young plants, they planted watermelons and
muskmelons in the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
