<HEADLINE> Aquatic Products Abundant in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, formerly facing a scarcity of fresh aquatic
products, now has surplus to send to inland areas.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in 1996, the region sent out 2,000 tons of
aquatic products to other areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous region, with average annual raindrop of less
than 147 mm, is one of the most drought hit areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
In the past, local residents could seldom find fresh aquatic
products on the market, as such products usually came from coastal
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Since the mid 1980s when the local government first eased the
control on aquatic products, the aquaculture industry has
witnessed rapid development.
</P>
<P>
Cities and prefectures in the region began to list fish
breeding as a priority in the strategy for the development of a
"vegetable basket", and to improve the living standards of local
residents. Inland farmers also rushed into the region to join the
efforts pushed by potential profits.
</P>
<P>
The aquatic products breeding area in the region has reached
73,000 hectares, generating some 50,000 tons of the products last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
