<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Denies Expelling Burundi Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 27 (Xinhua) -- President Benjamin Mkapa
denied Tanzania has expelled refugees to Burundi, thus resulting
in their being killed after their return home.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa made the denial after a local paper last Saturday
claimed that Mkapa had pledged to officials of Amnesty
International that Tanzania would not repeat forced repatriation
of Burundians since 122 out of 126 returned refugees had been
killed by the Burundi army.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Daily News today, State House
spokesman Patrick Chokala said here on Sunday that Mkapa told the
Amnesty International delegation last week that none of the
refugees had been expelled from this country.
</P>
<P>
They decided to return home on a voluntary basis, said the
Tanzanian president.
</P>
<P>
In the conversation, the spokesman said, Mkapa informed the
delegation that Burundi refugees in Tanzania had the option of
asking the United Nations High Commission for refugees to find
them another country of asylum other than Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"But they decided to return to Burundi, on their own free
will," he said, adding, "forceful repatriation of refugees is not
part of Tanzania's policy."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted Tanzania started accommodating refugees in
1959 and has an excellent record in its treatment of refugees,
acclaimed world-wide. Even in the case of Rwandan refugees, he
stressed, those returning home were doing so also voluntarily.
</P>
</TEXT>
