<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Tallest Building Receives 1st Batch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 of Occupants
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The world's tallest
building -- Malaysia's Petronas Twin Towers -- today received its
first batch of occupants -- 166 Petronas employees.
</P>
<P>
The employees from the central administrative unit and
Property Management Services Company Ltd. of the National
Petroleum Corporation moved in to occupy the 15th and 16th floors
of the 88-storeyed building with a height of 451.9 meters from the
street level.
</P>
<P>
One of the employees, who has served Petronas for 13 years,
said she was proud of being among the first to occupy the building
which has a futuristic design.
</P>
<P>
She said she was confident that the building was safe although
there had been negative claims about the safety.
</P>
<P>
Another employee said all her fears disappeared the moment she
set foot in the building.
</P>
<P>
Petronas Human Resources Vice-President Nordin Hassan
described at a reception the move-in as "historic" both for
Petronas and its staff as they would be occupying the world's
tallest building.
</P>
<P>
A Petronas spokesman said although the building had 88
storeys, only 86 floors could be occupied.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the 5,000-odd employees of Petronas and its
subsidiaries are expected to move into the building in stages by
August.
</P>
<P>
The 88-storey building, whose construction was started in
September, 1992, was completed at the end of last year. Its two
towers, each with an area of 218,000 square meters, are linked at
the 41st and 42nd floors by a skybridge and the building has
Islamic geometric features designed by world-renowned architect
Cesar Pelli.
</P>
<P>
Each tower has 29 double deck high speed passenger lifts.
</P>
<P>
The building is part of the 1 billion ringgit (about 400
million US dollars) Kuala Lumpur City Center (KLCC) integrated
project which is being developed.
</P>
<P>
The building is higher by 8.9 meters than the Sears Towers in
Chicago, United States, which were previously the world's tallest
buildings.
</P>
<P>
The twin towers are expected to be officially opened at the
end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
