<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Prevention Projects Beefed Up in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The ability to prevent and fight
floods has been greatly strengthened in southeast China's Fujian
Province, which frequently falls victim to natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government worked out a plan to fight natural
adversities in the late 1990s, according to Chen Guoliang, director
of the Provincial Department of Water Resources and Electric Power.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the governments of China and Japan have jointly
spent 220 million yuan building a flood alarm system on the
Minjiang River, the largest river in the province.
</P>
<P>
The system, the largest of its kind in China, became
operational before the flood season last year. The system's 98
monitoring stations cover an area of over 30,000 square kilometers
and quickly reflect rainfall and water levels in the area.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen, 4,800-kilometers of standard dykes will be
built along the river and coastal areas in the province. The
enhancing of 1,008-km of coastal dykes was completed late last
year, costing 730 million yuan from both government and unofficial
sources.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2.4 billion yuan will be spent on enhancing or
building dams along the rivers across the province. The provincial
financial department has arranged 40 million yuan for the project
this year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 78 reservoirs are under construction, involving an
investment of 3.8 billion yuan. There are now 2,896 reservoirs in
the province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
