<HEADLINE> High, New Technology Sector Becomes Industrial Pillar in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, January 27 (Xinhua) -- in southern Shenzhen's high
and new technology sector has turned out more than 30 billion yuan
in output value, becoming a pillar of the economy in the south
China city adjacent to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It accounted for 24 percent of Shenzhen's industrial production
last year, growing by 33 percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen in Guangdong province aims to boost the output value
of its high and new technology sector to 60 billion yuan by the
year 2000, or 35 percent of its industrial production.
</P>
<P>
The city at present boasts four high and new technology
developments, with 11 major businesses in the sector achieving an
output value over 18.4 billion yuan last year, making up over 60
percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment has played a vital role in development of
the local high and new technology, as evidenced by the fact that
all the 69 "enterprises with advanced technologies" recognized by
the local authorities recently were Sino-overseas joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
The electronic industry is one of the most successful in using
overseas funds in the sector.
</P>
<P>
With 18 consortia and multinationals such as Hitachi, IBM,
COMPAQ, Samsung, and Siemens investing in the industry, a
well-developed electronics industry has been established in
Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
And the city has become the biggest export base of computers
and support appliances in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
