<DOCNO> XIE19970127.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNEP Boss Complains About Financial Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Environmental Program
(UNEP) boss today complained about financial snags which she said
have hintered the implementation of its programs.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 19th session of the UNEP Governing Council
which opened here this morning, UNEP Executive Director Elizabeth
Dowdeswell said some programs approved at the 18th session cannot
be implemented as financial commitments have not been realized.
</P>
<P>
She told the two-week meeting that last year 18 states reduced
their contributions to the UNEP and three of them were major
contributors.
</P>
<P>
The UNEP boss stressed that whenever a decision is taken
jointly to pursue programs, full financing must be guaranteed and
secured.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Key western donors such as Japan, the
United States, Britain, France and Italy were reluctant to pay,
arguing that the UNEP set up in 1972 has become less effective
since the 1992 Earth Summit.
</P>
<P>
The UNEP budget dropped from 160 million U.S. Dollars in
1991-92 program to 105 million Dollars for 1996-97, but only 62.5
million was contributed by donors.
</P>
<P>
After listing a series of achievements in the past year,
Dowdeswell complained that "many view the UNEP as an organization
that has been marginalized over the years, losing much of its
credibility."
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that many of the difficulties experienced by
the UNEP are "stemming from factors that lie outside the scope of
the organization's immediate management control".
</P>
<P>
It is believed that financial difficulties facing the U.N.
environmental agency and structural reforms of the organization
will dominate the current session which takes place every two
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
