<HEADLINE> South Korea's Red Cross to Resume Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The (South) Korea National Red
Cross (KNRC) will resume its relief aid to the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) on January 30, a KNRC official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The relief goods, consisting of 300 tons of flour and 15,000 pares
of socks and other items worth about 180,000 U.S. dollars, will be
sent directly to Nampo Port in the DPRK from South Korea's western
port of Inchon.
</P>
<P>
This will be the 10th time for the KNRC to deliver relief goods
to the DPRK since it first launched the relief campaign in 1995 to
help the DPRK overcome the shortage of goods due to floods in two
consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the KNRC will send additional 700 tons of
flour worth 310,000 U.S. dollars to the DPRK on February 5.
</P>
<P>
Since September 1995, the KNRC has collected 2.43 million U.S.
dollars in donations for DPRK aid and has spent 1.73 million U.S.
dollars in sending flour, blankets, cooking oil, instant noodles
and other goods to the DPRK. 
</P>
</TEXT>
