<HEADLINE> Copyright Offenses Top Trade-related Offenses List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
in Malaysia in 1996
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Copyright infringements
topped the list of trade-related offenses last year in terms of
court-imposed fines.
</P>
<P>
According to Malaysian Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs
Ministry enforcement chief Abdul Jabar Kamin, of the total fines
of 727,380 ringgit (about 291,000 US dollars) paid for
trade-related offenses in 1996 against 580,370 ringgit (about
232,150 US dollars) in 1995, violations of the Copyright Act
contributed 505,965 ringgit (about 202,400 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The total fines collected last year for copyright offenses
were more than double the amount of 240,600 ringgit (about 96,240
US dollars) in 1995, he was quoted by Malaysia's official news
agency Bernama as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Jabar said the enforcement division would go all-out from this
year to curb copyright piracy and imitation goods to ensure the
success of the Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC) which seeks to
attract investments in state-of-the-art multimedia and information
technologies.
</P>
<P>
He urged intellectual property owners to assist the government
by identifying those who violate the copyright law so that
immediate action can be taken and to organize programs to educate
the public on copyright matters as well as to offer reward for
information on copyright infringement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
