<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Use Vote Counting Machines in Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Commission on
Elections (Comelec) will use vote counting machines in the 1998
general elections, Comelec officials said today.
</P>
<P>
Comelec Regional Director Felimon Asperin said the Comelec made
this decision under a law approved last year by Congress, which
stipulates the use of automated counting machines starting in
1998.
</P>
<P>
He said the government needs to spend some 900 million pesos
(34.4 million U.S. dollars) for buying such counting machines made
by an American firm for the more than 1,400 towns in the country.
</P>
<P>
Asperin said under the new counting system, voters will no
longer write the names of the candidates. They will only need to
blacken the oval space opposite the names of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
The new counting system will avoid spelling errors and assure
faster voting, he said, adding that it will help guarantee clean
and honest election as the machine will reject any fake ballot.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Comelec Regional Director Dominador Micu said vote
counting machines might be pilot-tested in some cities and towns
in local elections this May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
