<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Parliamentary Forum to Discuss Anti- </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Asia-Pacific Parliamentary
Forum (APPF) has accepted the Philippines' proposal to include the
anti-corruption issue in the agenda of its sixth annual meeting in
Seoul next year.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Senate majority leader Francisco Tatad said today
the 22-nation APPF will discuss the ways of combating official
corruption as proposed by Philippine delegates to the
just-concluded fifth APPF annual meeting in Canada.
</P>
<P>
"Rising corruption is not the only problem. More serious than
that is the growing public apathy and indifference to corruption,"
said Tatad, who headed the Philippine team to the APPF meeting in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
Tatad said the APPF meeting in Seoul "is probably the first
that official corruption and its effects on democracy and
development will be discussed in an international parliamentary
forum."
</P>
<P>
Official corruption has received very little attention in
international conferences despite its increasing adverse effects
on trade and investment, democracy and development as well as
national security, Tatad said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
