<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 09:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Turkey Wants Israeli Help in Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 27 (Xinhua) -- When Europe and the United
States hesitate to sell weapons to Turkey, Ankara turns to Israel
for help in its defense modernization, the Jerusalem Post reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The English daily quoted General Sitki Orun, technical adviser
to the Turkish Armed Forces Foundation, as announcing the request in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
Turkey needs Israeli contractors to fulfill its plan of 150
billion U.S. dollars over the next 25 years to modernize the
military. This includes new battle tanks, helicopters, jets and
ships, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This year most of the countries are decreasing military
budgets, but not Turkey," he said. The military budget has been
increased from 9 percent to 11 percent of the Turkish government
budget, according to Orun.
</P>
<P>
Orun complained that European countries and the United States
have hesitated selling weapons to Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Belgium canceled a weapons sale, following
a Norwegian arms embargo on Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department has been hesitating to grant an
export license for the AHIW Super Cobra attack helicopters
because of congressional concerns of Turkey's campaign against
rebel Kurds.
</P>
<P>
"If Belgium does not give us the weapons, we'll buy it from
some place else," Orun said. "These types of developments are to
the benefit of Israel."
</P>
<P>
Orun will be conducting meetings Monday and Tuesday in
efforts to recruit Israeli companies to participate in Turkey's
Defense Industry and Civil Aviation Fair in September. The fair is
sponsored by the government defense holding company Turkish Armed
Forces Foundation, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish general said that his government will examine the
Israel-made Merkava tank as part of its program to produce 800
battle tanks in a deal estimated at 3.2 billion dollars. Ankara
plans to begin co-production of a new type of tanks after the year
2000, preferring this to outright acquisition.
</P>
<P>
Orun said that another area Israel can participate in is that
of patrol and assault boats. Turkey is planning on acquiring 45
frigates, patrol ships and missile boats in its modernization
program.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been severely criticized by Arab countries and
Iran for signing a military cooperation pact with Israel last
year. The new Turkish Islamic government has watered down its
ties with the Jewish state since taking office.
</P>
<P>
However, Turkey has also come under harsh criticisms from the
European Union and the U.S. over its threats against Cyprus
following the island state's announcement to purchase Russian
missiles.
</P>
<P>
In view of the developments, Turkey is apparently attempting to
diversify its sources of arms acquisition, observers noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
