<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Concern About Unemployment in Israel's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli business leaders has
cautioned the government to deal properly with unemployment in
implementing its ambitious privatization plan.
</P>
<P>
Iscar Ltd. Chairman Stef Wertheimer told the English daily
The Jerusalem Post that the caution was needed to perform the
privatization process so as not to worry the work force.
</P>
<P>
Wertheimer's remarks came after the Prime Minister's Office
announced recently the sketchy details of the first group of
companies it hoped to sell during its term in office.
</P>
<P>
The privatization program should have been implemented two
years ago, but due to the concern about mass unemployment
the process might cause, the previous Labor government,
which maintained good relations with workers, failed to carry out
the plan.
</P>
<P>
Dan Propper, Chairman of Manufacturers Association, said that
if the Labor government had finished the privatization process
when the economy was at a stage of rapid growth, all those
losing their jobs would have been easily absorbed.
</P>
<P>
But now the economy was slowing down, and possibly heading
toward recession, so there could be problems for the work
force, namely a large increase in unemployment, Propper added.
</P>
<P>
He proposed a solution for the government: change the
monetary policy by the Bank of Israel so to spur economic
growth, which in turn would lead to heightened job creation.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sector has been urging the central bank to
lower interest rates, but was refused at a time when the
government is implementing a belt-tightening economic policy.
</P>
<P>
Leah Achdut, Director of Histadrut (Israel's General Trade
Union) Institute of Social and Economic Research, urged the
government to sit with employers and workers to decide
on the privatization method that will be of benefit to most
people.
</P>
<P>
The privatization plan has already caused widespread protests
from the labor camp, leading to several Histadrut-sponsored
nationwide strikes that have caused the economy dearly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
