<HEADLINE> East China Province Utilizing More Foreign Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Jiangsu province, east China,
has made an actual use of 21.4 billion U.S. dollars worth of
foreign funds, ranking second after Guangdong province in south
China.
</P>
<P>
Local officials attributed the success to the province's
efforts in improving the investment environment by investing
heavily in infrastructure. Jiangsu also adapted the province's
economic operations to international common practice by
implementing a modern enterprise system and economic globalization
strategy.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 alone, foreign investors paid in 5.56 billion
U.S. dollars in various projects they started in the east China
province, up 4.8 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Governments at local levels have made efforts to adjust the
foreign investment structure, and directed foreign funds to basic
industries, while having seen a decrease in moderate and small
processing industrial projects and a rise in large projects with
comparatively high technological contents.
</P>
<P>
Contracts involving an agreed use of 140 million U.S. dollars
of foreign funds have been signed for development of agricultural
projects, said local officials.
</P>
<P>
The province has won nine foreign-governmental loans, most of
which are given in support of construction of infrastructure and
social public projects.
</P>
<P>
Large state-owned enterprises in the province succeeded in
raising funds, by floating shares on domestic and overseas
bourses, according to the officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
