<HEADLINE> Southern Philippines to Build World's Best Railway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors have decided
to use the Japanese bullet train technology to build a railway in
the southern Philippines, government officials said today.
</P>
<P>
Hatimil Hassan, deputy chairman of the Southern Philippines'
Council for Peace and Development, said that with the Japanese
technology, the railway on Mindanao Island will be "comparable
with the best systems in the world."
</P>
<P>
He said a feasibility study for the railway system will be
completed by the middle of February.
</P>
<P>
According to Hassan, a transnational consortium comprising
Malaysian, Spanish, Australia and Indonesian investors has
initially put up 200 billion pesos (7.6 billion U.S. dollars) for
the project.
</P>
<P>
Hassan said a group of Japanese investors have also expressed
keen interest in joining the consortium.
</P>
<P>
The Mindanao railway project, which has already been approved
by the government, will link most provinces on the island and
provide cheap transport for both commuters and goods. 
</P>
