<HEADLINE> SADC Not to Allow Dual Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSKA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African Development
Community (SADC) will not allow its members to indefinitely
continue to be members of the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA), "the post" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian newspaper quoted SADC Information Officer
Kgoesinki Moesi as saying that member states holding the dual
membership will not be allowed as this will hinder SADC's smooth
operations.
</P>
<P>
He also denied a possible merger of the two regional bodies,
saying, "we want to develop a common market and merging is not an
answer."
</P>
<P>
As to the recent decision to withdraw from the COMESA by
Lesotho and Mozambique, Moesi said the two countries are just
implementing an undertaking they made two years ago to choose
between the two institutions.
</P>
<P>
"Time will come when a deadline will be set to force members
to decide which organization they want to belong to," he added.
</P>
<P>
Of 12 SADC members, only Botswana and South Africa are not
members of the 20-member COMESA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
