<HEADLINE> China to Speed Up Technical Development to Protect Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China is to invest 500 million
yuan annually to develop environmental technology in the last few
years of this century, equaling the total of the Eighth Five-Year
Plan period (1991-1995).
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Ye Ruqiu, deputy director of the State
Bureau of Environment Protection, today at a press conference to
give details of the "'97 China Environment Forum".
</P>
<P>
Ye said that enterprises in China should become another source
of investment in the development of environmental technology,
instead of depending on funds from the government.
</P>
<P>
Emphasis should be put on technical research to harness
industrial pollution by the year 2000, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Major polluted areas, such as the rivers of Huaihe, Haihe, and
Liaohe, and the lakes of Taihu, Chaohu, and Dianchi, are badly in
need of advanced technology to eliminate pollution, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
According to a blueprint by the State Bureau of Environment
Protection, China expects to bring the aggravating tendency in
environmental protection and ecological destruction basically
under control by the end of this century. Improvement will be
achieved in the environmental quality of cities and regions.
</P>
<P>
The "97 Environment Forum" is the first international
environment symposium sponsored by non-government organizations in
China, focusing on research into the coordinated development of
the country's economy, social progress, and environmental
protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
