<HEADLINE> Taliban Take Steps to Secure Newly-captured Valley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
have deployed another 3,000 soldiers to secure a newly-captured
key valley linking Kabul to the opposition-held north, reports
reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic student militia have taken control of the Ghorband
valley, 70 kilometers northwest of Kabul, Radio Shariat in Kabul
reported.
</P>
<P>
The report, which was aired on Sunday and could not be
independently confirmed, said about 2,000 opposing soldiers had
defected.
</P>
<P>
The capture of the Ghorband valley gives the Taliban an easier
route to advance into the northern provinces controlled by warlord
Rashid Dostum and former military chief Ahmad Massood.
</P>
<P>
The direct route to northern Afghanistan through the Salang
Tunnel is controlled by Dostum's troops and is a difficult area to
penetrate.
</P>
<P>
The Salang Tunnel is the final gateway through the Hindu Kushi
mountains to his northern stronghold.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban now control roughly two-thirds of the country,
while the opposition forces control the northern one-third.
</P>
</TEXT>
