<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu's Foreign Trade Surges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
recorded 19.9 billion U.S. dollars worth of imports and exports
in 1996, up more than a fifth over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Exports made up 13.1 billion U.S. dollars, a rise of 13.8
percent over 1995 and 12.34 percentage points higher than the
national average, making Jiangsu China's third largest exporter.
Imports were worth 6.77 billion U.S. dollars, up 35.13 percent.
</P>
<P>
The fast growth in foreign trade was made possible because the
province intensified its efforts to break the monopoly of foreign
trade by state and provincial foreign trade professional
companies, and encouraged enthusiasm in foreign trade services.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, all 13 cities directly administered by
the provincial government and 64 counties and county-level cities
have been given the authority to manage foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers with fine conditions have also been given the
autonomy to handle imports and exports, and directly participate
in international trade, which has in turn helped improve operation
vitality and competitiveness of the enterprises.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, 502 large and medium-sized enterprises
had been given the authority to directly manage imports and exports.
The enterprises exported 1.33 billion U.S. dollars of commodities
last year, a rise of 38.5 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu now has more than 30,000 foreign-backed enterprises
which are also playing a leading role in boosting the province's
exports.
</P>
<P>
They exported 5.5 billion U.S. dollars worth of commodities in
1996, up 34 percent over 1995, and accounting for one quarter of
the province's total export volume for 1996.
</P>
<P>
While encouraging more economic entities to participate in
foreign trade, the province has also paid close attention to the
quality of export commodities and the economic benefits of foreign
trade companies.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, the ratio of certification of
export commodities for inspection last year was 99 percent, and
from January to November last year foreign trade firms earned
32.13 million yuan (one U.S. dollars equals to 8.3 Chinese yuan)
in profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
