<HEADLINE> Researches Done on Asparagus in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- A series of studies have been
done in Uganda on asparagus and will be completed by the end of
this year, "The New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
D. S. Osiru, head of Department of Crop Science and Production
at Makerere University, said the researches have been done in
Uganda concerning appraisal of varieties of the crop, optimum
spacing, fertilizer application, disease control, yield and
post-harvest handling.
</P>
<P>
Asparagus was introduced into Uganda in 1960's, but failed due
to lack of knowledge. It was reintroduced with the help of the
U.S. Agency for International Development and now is considered
as one of the potential supplement crops for export.
</P>
<P>
The studies were launched early last year by Makerere
University and Fort Valley State College in Georgia of the United
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
