<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Wrong Decision Responsibility System" to Be Tried Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation is to try out a system in which
leading officials of state-owned enterprises will take
responsibility for making wrong decisions.
</P>
<P>
Details of the trial were announced in an article in the
Beijing-based magazine "Outlook" which published here today.
</P>
<P>
The system will first be tried on an experimental basis at some
designated enterprises in Shanghai and Guangzhou cities and
central China's Hunan province this year.
</P>
<P>
The move will play a positive role in enhancing leading
officials' sense of responsibility and cutting down the number of
blind decisions, the article said, adding that other trades and
departments should use it as a reference.
</P>
<P>
The article criticized some leading officials who had given no
thought to the interests of the state, collectives and the people,
and who failed to conduct careful investigations in making
decisions.
</P>
<P>
They often depended on "inspiration" and made unrealistic
decisions which wasted money and manpower.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, improper or wrong decisions by leading
officials in some areas have caused inestimable losses to the
state and the people, it said.
</P>
<P>
It advised leading officials to be more pragmatic rather than
subjective in making decisions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
