<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Continue Electoral Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
continue to implement its massive electoral reform program,
Philippine President Fidel Ramos said here today.
</P>
<P>
Ramos told the delegates from more than 20 countries attending
a symposium organized by the International Foundation for Election
System and the Commission on Elections of the Philippines that
beginning this year, all voters will register anew and this will
be on a continuing basis.
</P>
<P>
The government has embarked on a massive electoral reform
program, he said, including the installation of modern computers
to speed up the tabulation of votes and eliminate fraud in
preparation for the 1998 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Voters will be issued voter's ID cards that will help reduce
the incidence of electoral fraud.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Commission on Election put in place the
beginning of a computerized electoral process that "will allow us
to take advantage of new technologies to greatly speed up the
counting process," the President said.
</P>
<P>
He said he is looking forward to the day when all electoral
processes are computerized for an instantaneous tabulation of
electoral results.
</P>
<P>
The President said this will be a major progression from the
elections that brought him to office in 1992, "where the
tabulation of results required nearly six weeks of suspenseful
counting, canvassing, proclamation -- and waiting."
</P>
<P>
The symposium held at the Diamond Hotel is aimed at laying the
foundations for an Asian regional organization of officials
responsible for the election process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
