<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Establishes More Hospices For Old People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
city, has built 30 hospices to strengthen its care service for its
growing population of elderly people.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has a population of 13 million, including 2.2 million
people at over 60 years of age -- 17 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Though most of the old people in Shanghai are in good health,
150,000 people aged at over 70 are unable to take care of
themselves because of serious illness or the after-effect of
strokes, senile dementia, and terminal cancer.
</P>
<P>
In most cases the spouses of sick old people are also too old
to take care of their partners, and their children are busily
engaged in their work.
</P>
<P>
Since 1988, the city began to build hospices that receive old
people with serious diseases. Now Shanghai's hospices have over
1,500 hospital beds.
</P>
<P>
The hospices provide medical, nursing and psychological
services.
</P>
<P>
Wang Suqin, an 85-year-old dementia sufferer, is living in
Jing'an Hospital for the aged people. Her niece said the hospital
has a good environment and nurses are very kind to patients there,
adding that her aunt is in better condition after receiving
treatment in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
More old people are changing their idea of "living at home
until their last days" and prefer to live in the hospices when
they can not take care of themselves, even though they have
children who are willing to take care of them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
