<HEADLINE> China Shifting Textile Industry to Northwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China has taken its first step
to transfer part of the country's textile industry from its
eastern regions to the west.
</P>
<P>
Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region has started
five projects which will expand the region's cotton spinning
production.
</P>
<P>
The projects, which will increase spinning capacity by 261,000
spindles, are the result of cooperation between the region's
backbone textile enterprises and the country's traditional textile
industrial bases, such as Shanghai, Beijing, east China's Shandong
province, and southwest China's Sichuan province.
</P>
<P>
The move is regarded as China's first step to transfer the
major part of the textile industry to the west, where the
country's major cotton production bases are located.
</P>
<P>
China will shift 500,000 spindles of cotton spinning into the
hinterland region during the ninth five-year plan period
(1996-2000), in a bid to build Xinjiang into the largest
manufacturer of cotton yarn and cloth in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
China's State Development Bank (SDB) will allocate 750 million
yuan in loans for the drive, which has been jointly launched by
the China National Textile Council and the State Planning
Commission.
</P>
<P>
So far, 200 million yuan of SDB's loans have been poured into
the region, which is the leading cotton producer in China, and
turned out over one million tons of cotton in 1996, accounting for
25 percent of the country's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
