<DOCNO> XIE19970127.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Kwazulu/Natal Premier Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 27 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's
Kwazulu/Natal Premier and Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP) National
Chairman Frank Mdlalose will step down from both posts in late
February, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
Mdlalose's resignation, which came out as a surprise not only
to the public but also to most IFP members, was accepted by the
IFP's National Council in Ulundi at the weekend, said the source.
</P>
<P>
Mdlalose, 65, a founder member of the IFP, cited ill-health
for his resignation, but there is a strong speculation that the
real reason is connected to tensions between him and Party
President Mangosuthu Buthelezi.
</P>
<P>
The pressure on Mdlalose has been unbearable following
Buthelezi's recent attack on unnamed leaders whom he said are
more interested in drawing publicity to themselves than in
building the party.
</P>
<P>
Following Mdlalose's announcement of resignation, Buthelezi
said in a statement that the premier has indicated that because
of personal reasons, he will not be prepared to lead the party in
the 1999 electoral campaign acting both as IFP chairman and
Kwazulu/Natal premier.
</P>
<P>
Ben Ngubane, 55, currently provincial finance minister, will
step into Mdlalose's shoes as acting chairman of the party and
Kwazulu/Natal premier.
</P>
<P>
Kwazulul/Natal, heart-base to the country's largest tribal
group Zulu, is the only province controlled by the IFP in South
Africa's nine provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
