<DOCNO> XIE19970127.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Pour Huge Investment into Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China is to invest 1.5 percent
of its gross national product (GNP) in environmental protection
in the remaining years of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
It will mean the country spending an average 65 billion yuan
annually on "green' projects.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Ye Ruqiu, deputy director of the State
Bureau of Environment Protection (SBEP), at a press conference
today in advance of the '97 China Environment Forum.
</P>
<P>
The event is the first international environmental protection
symposium to be sponsored by China's non-governmental
organizations, and is scheduled for February 24-27 in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that the funds will be used to build new environmental
protection projects, control old pollution sources with advanced
technology, and construct basic environmental protection
facilities in cities, and strengthen natural protection.
</P>
<P>
Emphasis will be given to control water pollution in the
Huaihe, Haihe, and Liaohe rivers, and the lakes of Taihu, Chaohu,
and Dianchi, he said.
</P>
<P>
The funding will come mainly from central and local
governments, domestic and overseas banks, and local enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the SBEP plans to absorb some foreign funds, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China invested nearly 40 billion yuan
annually on average in environmental protection during the Eighth
Five-Year Plan period (1991-1995), accounting for about 0.8
percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
According to a blueprint by SBEP, China will bring the
aggravating tendency in environment pollution and ecological
destruction basically under control by the end of this century,
with a marked improvement of environment quality seen in cities
and regions.
</P>
<P>
However, Ye pointed out, China still faces a grim environmental
situation, with a negative influence on social and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, environment pollution is taking a turn for
the worse in urban areas, and is stretching into the
countryside. The range of ecological destruction is widening, he
warned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
