<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970127.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trains to Run Faster in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Major inter-city rail journeys
in China will be quicker from April when train speeds are
increased to more than 110 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
The faster trains will run on rail journeys starting from the
cities of Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Chengdu, Zhengzhou, Wuhan,
and Xi'an, most of them long distance journeys of between 1,000
kilometers and 1,500 km.
</P>
<P>
And by the start of the new century, China will have taken
delivery of 64 "arrive-in-a-night" long-distance passenger trains,
Zhou Yimin, deputy chief engineer of the Ministry of Railways,
told Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
Included are 11 pairs of such trains to be started this year,
including the Beijing-Dalian and Beijing-Qingdao trains, he said.
</P>
<P>
Low-standard marketing and service, and the low speeds of
trains in China are factors that have caused a drop in passenger
transport of railway, Zhou pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that trains carried a total of 942 million
travelers last year, a 12.3 percent drop over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railways will launch more "return-in-a-day"
trains within a distance of 200 to 400 kilometers, as part of
efforts to enhance the attraction of rail transport to
travelers, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Such trains already run on some rail sections, including
Beijing-Beidaihe and Shanghai-Nanjing. The railway line from
Zhengzhou to Wuhan will soon witness such a pair of trains,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Ministry of Railways will put into operation a
batch of tourist trains, holiday trains, as well as special trains
for rural people working in cities, and football specials will be
started for fans.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that the speed of cargo trains will also be raised to
about 80 km per hour from 60 km per hour, to match the raised
speeds of passenger trains and to ensure the safety on rail
tracks. 
</P>
