<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economic Climate to Further Improve This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China's overall economic
climate is expected to move between the green light and yellow
light zones this year, coupled with an expected stable and
improving national economic performance in 1997, according to a
forecast by the State Statistics Bureau today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, individual industrial enterprises are likely to
enjoy a more favorable performance this year.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Xiaohua, spokesman for the bureau, said that China's
overall economic climate went through an upward spiral in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He said that the business climate, feelings of individual
companies about their performance, was basically stable last year,
with its four quarterly indicators moving within a range of minus
0.07 and a positive 0.06. He added that the fluctuation was
smaller than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Qiu said that the business climate for state-owned enterprises
(SOEs) continued to be poorer than that for the non-state sector,
but the gap has narrowed.
</P>
<P>
"The fourth quarterly business climate indicator stood at 0.06
for SOEs and that for non-SOEs was 0.08," he said, "but the
indicators were minus 0.03 and a positive 0.06 respectively for
the same quarter in 1995."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that serious problems remain in the
economic climate.
</P>
<P>
"The allocation of resources is not radical," he
said. "Redundant and blind construction has not been effectively
curbed, which hampers economic efficiency."
</P>
<P>
"For instance, 23 of the 30 provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions have their own automobile plants. But the
national total of 1.45 million units is even less than one-quarter
of a major car company abroad," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, poor industrial economic efficiency continues to be
a sore spot in the Chinese economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
A quarter of the country's industrial enterprises are
money-losing and 43.7 percent of the state-owned enterprises are
not profitable. The rate is five percentage points higher than the
previous year, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
