<HEADLINE> Bronze Items Unearthed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Archeologists have unearthed
255 bronze items used by members of the court from an ancient
kingdom in China's Spring and Autumn Period (770-476 BC).
</P>
<P>
The artifacts were discovered during an excavation of the site
of the ancient capital city of Zheng in central China's Henan
Province, between December last year and January 20 this year.
</P>
<P>
It is unusual for archeologists to unearth so many bronze items
during one excavation, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The unearthed items, which include bronze tripods, vases and
cauldrons, will be valuable to the study of ritual systems in the
Spring and Autumn Period, when China was transforming from a
slave-owning system to a feudalist society.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970127.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pesticide Abuse in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 27 (Xinhua) -- A University of Zimbabwe (UZ)
agronomist said the abuse of pesticides in the country has
reached alarming proportions and warned this poses a serious
threat to human health.
</P>
<P>
UZ deputy Dean of Agriculture Austin Chivinge said on Sunday
that many people were either applying wrong chemicals for the
wrong crop or over-applying certain chemicals on crops.
</P>
<P>
''Some people are spraying insecticides to control diseases,
instead of using a fungicide,'' he said, adding that this was
most prevalent in horticultural production among small-holder
farmers.
</P>
<P>
He said many people did not observe the safety regulations on
the use of chemicals, neither did they use protective clothing
like gloves, gorgles and gum-boots, thereby exposing themselves to
the highly dangerous chemicals.
</P>
<P>
''This normally results in acute poisoning which ends up in
death and the worst one is chronic poisoning, where one is being
poisoned gradually and only realizing this much later when health
problems begin to affect the individual,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Chivinge said casinogenic or cancerous diseases could also
result from pesticides abuse, adding that sterility could also
result.
</P>
<P>
Chemicals should be stored separately in locked-up places
where there were no foodstuffs, he said.
</P>
<P>
''There is also a need for a lot of education for pesticides
users on both the benefits of using and the problems associated
with using, such as pollution of water and other environments, as
well as education on the need to intensify the safety aspect,''
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
