<HEADLINE> Regional Trade Increases in Southern Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Intra-regional trade in
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) has increased
by 12.4 percent in the past two years, said a SADC report.
</P>
<P>
Local daily "The Citizen" today quoted SADC sources as saying
that the report was released in Gaborone, capital of Botswana on
Sunday and planned to be submitted to a SADC consultative
conference in Namibia's capital Windhoek early next month.
</P>
<P>
It cited peace and stability and the introduction of trade
liberalization measures as main contributions to the trade
increase.
</P>
<P>
SADC member states have been trading in agricultural products,
mining, food products, textiles, clothing, beverages, wood
products and industrial chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The report said, however, inadequate production base,
insufficient trade policies and market access, underdeveloped
financial infrastructure and inadequate trade statistics and
information are still obstacles to trade in the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another report on trade and industry, also to be
submitted to the forthcoming SADC conference, identified low
savings, exchange control regulations, high investment risks and
low returns as obstacles to the increase of the investment in the
region.
</P>
<P>
SADC comprises Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius,
Mozambique, Namibia, Tanzania, South Africa, Swaziland, Zambia
and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
