<HEADLINE> China Zoo Wants Adoptive 'Parents' For Its Animals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, January 27 (Xinhua) -- People in China are to be given
the chance to adopt a cuddly giant panda.
</P>
<P>
The move has been taken by a zoo in northwest China's Gansu
Province which has invited individuals and organisations to adopt
its vast collection of rare animals.
</P>
<P>
Most of the animals seeking adoptive parents at the zoo in the
provincial capital of Lanzhou are under state or world-level
protection.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, sponsoring organizations or individuals can
choose one or several animals at the zoo and help towards the cost
of raising them, according to the Lanzhou City Zoo.
</P>
<P>
The zoo will post a board containing the sponsor's name on the
cage of the animal, and each sponsor will also be allowed to name
the animal, said an official.
</P>
<P>
The zoo will also release regular reports to sponsors on the
condition and progress of the animals they are supporting.
</P>
<P>
Gansu is home to 80 kinds of rare animals under national
protection, including the giant panda and the takin, with Lanzhou
City Zoo now raising 22 types of animals on the verge of
extinction.
</P>
<P>
Since China ratified the "Convention on Bio-Diversity" in 1992,
an important international environmental regulation formulated by
many countries in the world, a large number of cities in the
country including Shanghai, Tianjin and Guangzhou have called on
the public to contribute to the protection of rare animals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
