<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Government, Rebels Seem Close to Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government and
the tribal rebels in Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) seem poised for
striking an agreement when their peace talks entered the third
consecutive day today, according to meeting sources.
</P>
<P>
"The difference between the two sides to resolve the issues is
gradually narrowing to reach an agreement," the sources said,
adding that Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina on Sunday night was
briefed on the talks.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying for an agreement. We've come for an agreement,"
said Chittagong Mayor Abm Mohiuddin Chowdhury, who is also a
member of the National Committee on CHI which is negotiating with
the Parbatya Chattagram Jana Sanghati Samity (PCJSS), political
wing of the armed Buddhist rebels in CHT.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have been fighting a bush war since 1973 for
autonomy of the resource-rich hill forests in Southeast
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Today's talks are to center around three crucial points of the
rebels' demand -- land distribution, Bangalee settlers and local
government structure in the three hill districts, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, nine rounds of talks were held since a cease-fire was
reached in August 1992 between the government and the tribal
rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
