<HEADLINE> China Becomes Second Biggest Trade Partner of Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China has become the second
largest trade partner of Mongolia, with their two-way trade volume
reaching 140 million U.S. dollars in 1996, a Mongolian official
told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Nazhengova, deputy director of the International Trade and
Cooperation Bureau under the Ministry of External Relations, said
the figure accounted for 16 percent of Mongolia's total foreign
trade.
</P>
<P>
Since the normalization of the relations between the two
countries, both governments have made efforts to develop
cooperation in economy and trade.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, there are more than 170 Sino-Mongolian joint
ventures in Mongolia, accounting for 30 percent of the total,
which made China a country that operates the largest number of
joint ventures in the land-locked country, she said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has provided Mongolia with 130 million
yuan in soft loans since 1990 to help the country overcome crisis
during its transition to a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Both sides are working on 16 cooperative projects funded by the
loans, including those in coal mine, trade service centers and
leather processing plants. The other eight projects will be
completed within 1997, she added.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, China gave Mongolia 3 million yuan of commodities in
aid, plus a 20-million-yuan free loan to help Mongolia fight a big
forestry fire, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
