<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Capital Inflows Into Thailand Ease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Foreign capital inflows into
Thailand slowed down last year, with long-term loans outpacing
short-term ones.
</P>
<P>
According to data from the Thai Central Bank available today,
Thailand's outstanding external debt was posted at 88.96 billion
U.S. dollars in November last year, rising by only 7.7 percent
over 1995.
</P>
<P>
Of the debt, foreign loans longer than one year accounted for
55.4 percent, higher than the 50.2 percent seen at the end of
1995.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Central Bank's measures introduced last April to curb
inflows of short-term loans might contribute to the healthier
borrowing situation in the country last year.
</P>
<P>
The central bank now requires commercial banks to place a
7-percent cash reserve when they get foreign debts with a maturity
less than one year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's foreign borrowing totaled 82.56 billion dollars in
1995, jumping nearly 27.3 percent from 1994.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970127.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget Cut to Trim Inflation: Thai Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The central bank of Thailand
believes that if the government's austerity policy succeeds, the
country's inflation this year could drop to 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
To curb the current account deficit, the government plans to
defer government spending for 1997 of more than 50 billion baht (2
billion U.S. dollars) in non-productive projects and intends to
slash the 1998 budget by another 50 billion baht.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's fiscal 1998 begins in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
For the past two years inflation has been relatively high,
standing at 5.8 percent in 1995 and 5.9 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
For 1997, the Bank of Thailand predicts that a higher
agricultural output should dampen food prices, a major
contribution to inflation.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year, the central bank predicted that
inflation for 1997 would drop considerably to 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The National Economic and Social Development Board is working
out basic criteria for slashing unnecessary projects from the
budget.
</P>
<P>
Board Secretary-General Wirat Watanasiritham said projects to
be axed would be those deemed unproductive, overly luxurious or
those with high import content. Projects which do not complement
current projects would also be cut.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thawatchai Yongkitikul, secretary-general of the
Thai Bankers' Association, said the government should especially
concentrate on reducing spending on imports rather than cutting
investment projects affecting domestic employment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
