<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More People Killed in Philippines' Military Clashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government troops and
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) continued their clashes,
killing eight more people on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides were still battling despite a temporary local
cease-fire declared by higher military and MILF leaders, bringing
the death toll to 41 since the start of the fighting last
Thursday, the newspaper Manila Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
They began crossfire after the rebels attacked Buldon Mayor
Macarampat Manalao and his escorts near one of the MILF's main
camps in Maguindanao Province in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The MILF claimed that all the dead in the latest fighting were
soldiers and that only one rebel was wounded. The military had no
comment on the same day.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Social Welfare and Development said some
2,000 families have already fled the area and evacuation still
continued due to the unabated fighting.
</P>
<P>
However, another local newspaper, Today, reported that
negotiators from the two warring sides agreed on a six-point pact
on Sunday for the cessation of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
Ghazali Jaafar, MILF political affairs chief, was quoted as
saying the two sides' representatives are slated to sign the
agreement today in Sultan Kudarat town, where they held their
first round of low-level peace talks last month.
</P>
<P>
The agreement provides that the MILF and the military will
maintain the respective positions of their troops and no
additional deployment will be allowed, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Both the MILF and the military agreed not to take any
provocative action such as ambushes, bombardments and similar acts
relative to military combat operations, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
The MILF also agreed not to set up blocking forces or
checkpoints along a highway near the town of Buldon to prevent the
military from being provoked, it said.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a 12,000-member breakaway faction of the mainstream
Moro National Liberation Front which concluded a peace agreement
with the government last year, is scheduled to have its second
round of peace talks with the government peace panel on February
25-26.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
