<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Becomes World's Major Corn Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China has become the world's
major producer of corn, with production amounting to 100 million
tons in 1996, researchers have reported.
</P>
<P>
The figure accounted for one-fifth of the world's total output.
</P>
<P>
Experts credit China's success with effective measures against
natural disasters and progress in processing industry.
</P>
<P>
The planting area of corn covers 20 million hectares in China,
about 15 percent of the country's arable land.
</P>
<P>
Three major corn production regions stretch almost across the
country, from southern most Hainan Island to the northern most
Heilongjiang Province, from Taiwan to northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said that about 27 percent of the planting area is
in the northeast China's Jilin, Heilongjiang and Liaoning
provinces and north China's Hebei Province, where corn is seeded
in spring.
</P>
<P>
About 40 percent is on the plains between Yellow River and
Huaihe River in east China's Shandong and Jiangsu provinces and
central China's Henan Province, where corn is seeded either
in spring or in summer time.
</P>
<P>
One-fourth of the corn is planted on hilly land in southwest
China's Yunnan, Guizhou and Sichuan provinces.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have seen their efforts in improving corn
planting techniques pay off, as the per hectare output of the corn
has risen to 7,500 kilograms as against 1,350 kg in 1949, when new
China was founded.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, China has cultivated and introduced many
strains of good-quality corn, some of which can be made into tasty
and nutritious food, and some can be used as raw material for
industry.
</P>
<P>
"Corn can be processed into 500 different kinds of products,
and can be used as basic material for some hi-tech products," said
an expert in the study of corn.
</P>
<P>
As the corn output rises and the techniques of corn processing
improve, corn is no longer only used as food in China, but also
can be used as feed and as a resource in industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
