<HEADLINE> Floods Force Thousands to Leave Homes in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Floods, caused by heavy rains,
forced the evacuation of thousands of people from their homes on
Saturday and Sunday in the Central Java town of Kendal, Indonesia,
the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of hectares of farmland and rice paddies, buildings,
schools and roads were swamped in the town by flood waters up to
two meters deep, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The main coastal road, which runs through Kendal to the
provincial capital Semarang, was hampered by the floods causing a
traffic backlog.
</P>
<P>
Kendal, which is 60 kilometers west of Semarang, saw thousands
of its residents pack their belongings and sought dry ground on
roofs and tall buildings.
</P>
<P>
Waters up to 1.7 meters deep inundated the town's central
market, the attorney general's department and other government
buildings.
</P>
<P>
Police said the flood waters began to drop Sunday morning,
although some of the farming areas are still under half a meter of
water.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been hard-hit by heavy rains this month, which is
the middle of the wet season here.
</P>
<P>
Last week two people were reported missing and thousands of
people had to be evacuated from their homes in areas close to
Kendal as flash floods hit Semarang and surrounding districts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
