<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: U.S. to Continue Policies on Missile Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said today he would carry out the administration's
policies and promote a "three-plus-three" formula on an
anti-missile system.
</P>
<P>
Under the formula worked out by Cohen's predecessor, William
Perry, the Pentagon would research the concept of a national
defense system until 2000, and then decide whether the threat
warrants deployment by 2003.
</P>
<P>
Republicans have demanded immediate efforts to erect a national
anti-missile defense system, a new version of the Strategic
Defense Initiative sought during the Reagan presidency.
</P>
<P>
The administration has countered that it would be inordinately
expensive, unnecessary and a violation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile treaty.
</P>
<P>
On ABC's "This Week" program, Cohen said he was not sure if it
was technically possible to install a system by 2003 and that it
would not be designed for all-out nuclear war but "to give us
protection against limited, isolated or perhaps accidental
missiles."
</P>
<P>
Cohen also urged the Senate to ratify a treaty banning chemical
weapons. He said that failure to join other countries in the
international convention could isolate the United States and
result in serious economic losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970127.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Expand Medicine Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Every town in China will have a
medicine retail shop or medical pharmacy by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The State Pharmaceutical Administration has vowed to build
38,000 medicine retail networks in the next four years, double the
current number, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Currently there are 19,000 medical retail shops in the
countryside, or one for 2.5 towns on average.
</P>
<P>
Once the targets are fulfilled, a state-managed pharmaceutical
wholesale and retail network will cover all counties, towns and
villages and provide safe and high-quality medicines for rural
people, especially those living in poor and remote villages.
</P>
<P>
In China, counties and towns near cities often get medicines
from state pharmaceutical wholesale stores and their subordinated
commercial centers. Some township hospitals, village supply and
marketing cooperatives also sell medicines.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the administration suggested that over 900
million people living in rural areas consume only one quarter of
the medicines in the country each year. The ratio of average
consumption of medicines and use of medical equipment per person
between farmers and urbanities is one to nine.
</P>
<P>
The average expenditure on medicine per person will go up to
some 30 yuan (about 3.6 U.S. dollars) among rural people by the
year 2000, said experts, due to the improvement of health care
services and a changing concept on health. The current figure is
17 yuan (about two U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
