<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Li Peng recently expressed his concern about
the workers at a large state-owned enterprise in the old
industrial city of Anshan, in northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
During an inspection tour from January 23 to 25, Li warmly
greeted employees and visited the homes of some model workers. He
said that the Communist Party of China and the Chinese government
work in the interests of the people, and officials at various
levels should help to solve the problems of the people, especially
those in state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In Anshan, Li inspected a number of state firms, including the
Anshan Iron and Steel Company, a steel production giant employing
500,000 people, 120,000 of whom are retirees.
</P>
<P>
-- The All-China Journalists Association (ACJA) made an
announcement to encourage public supervision over journalists. The
Propaganda Department of the Central Committee of the Communist
Party of China, the Ministry of Radio, Film and Television and the
ACJA jointly banned paid news service on January 23.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The per capita net income of Chinese farmers in 1996 reached
1,900 yuan, hitting an all-time high since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented a 20 percent rise over that in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Economists said a good harvest was a major factor contributing
to the rise in farmers' incomes. Last year each farmer earned
50 yuan more from increased grain production alone.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of farmers' income comes from agricultural
production.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun has called on local officials in
Hunan and Anhui provinces to show more concern for the farmers who
suffered from last year's heavy floods.
</P>
<P>
During his inspection tour of the area from January 22 to 25,
Jiang visited five villages and praised farmers for their efforts
to rebuild their homes.
</P>
<P>
He urged local officials to ensure that every disaster-affected
rural family has enough food, clothing and housing so that they
can enjoy the Spring Festival, which falls on February 7.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Rita Fan Hsu Lai-tai became the president of the Provisional
legislative Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) Saturday.
</P>
<P>
-- The number and quality of Chinese lawyers and law firms
gained rapid progress last year thanks to effective reforms,
Justice Minister Xiao Yang told China Daily over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers across the country totaled nearly 100,000 by the end
of last year while the figure was 40,000 in 1993. The number of
law firms increased to 7,5000 in 1996 from 3,000 in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
