<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reports Rapid Progress in Law Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China's Minister of Justice
Xiao Yang said that the number and quality of Chinese lawyers and
law firms gained rapid progress in 1996, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Beijing-based English newspaper, Xiao
revealed that lawyers across the country totalled nearly 100,000
by the end of last year, while the figure was merely 40,000 in
1993.
</P>
<P>
The number of law firms increased to 7,500 in 1996 from 3,000
in 1993, and to date, 80 percent of the lawyers have higher-level
academic degrees, he added.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Chinese lawyers handled 700,000 lawsuits and
non-lawsuits, more than double that of 1993. They also provided
better services for more government agencies and enterprises as
legal consultants than in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Xiao pointed out that six reform measures were carried out last
year on the basis of the previous years' efforts to bring the
lawyer's system closer to international standards.
</P>
<P>
The measures include redefinition of the organization of law
firms, improvement of the lawyer management system, promulgation
of new laws and regulations concerning lawyers, promotion of the
legal assistance system, and establishment of the lawyer
qualification examination system and a reasonable income
distribution system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
