<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Wins All-Star Voting in Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordan, one of world
basketball all-time greats, on Sunday became the first player to
receive more than 2 million votes for the NBA All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
In final fan voting for the February 9 game at Cleveland, the
Chicago Bulls guard led all players in votes for a record eighth
time with 2,451,136. He will be playing in his 11th All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
Joining Jordan in the Eastern Conference starting lineup will
be forwards Grant Hill of Detroit (1,868,020 votes) and Scottie
Pippen of Chicago (1,683,956), center Patrick Ewing of New York
(1,395,759) and guard Penny Hardaway of Orlando (1,132,024).
</P>
<P>
For the Western Conference, the starters will be forwards
Charles Barkley of Houston (1,877,232) and Shawn Kemp of Seattle
(1,713,049), center Hakeem Olajuwon of Houston (1,487,310) and
guards Gary Payton of Seattle (1,206,539) and John Stockton of
Utah (1,127,250).
</P>
<P>
The rest of the two teams will be selected by the two coaches
and announced this week. Houston's Rudy Tomjanovich will coach the
West and Pat Riley of Miami or Doug Collins of Detroit will coach
the East.
</P>
<P>
During his career, Jordan has received 12,009,832 votes. He
also led the voting for seven consecutive seasons (1987-1993),
before Barkley ended his streak in 1994. Hill was the top
vote-getter in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
This will be the 12th All-Star appearance for Olajuwon, the
11th each for Ewing and Barkley, the ninth for Stockton, the
seventh for Pippen, the fifth for Kemp, the fourth for Payton and
the third each for Hill and Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
The East leads the All-Star series 29-17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
