<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Severely Punish Misuse of Three Gorges Resettlement Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China will severely punish the
improper use of funds issued for the resettlement of the gigantic
Three Gorges Project, the world's largest water-control endeavor.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Project Construction Commission under the
State Council will set up a supervision bureau to improve
management of the resettlement fund.
</P>
<P>
"China has imposed strict management on the Three Gorges
resettlement fund," said Qi Lin, director of the commission's
Resettlement and Development Bureau.
</P>
<P>
By 2009, China will have to relocate around 1.2 million people
and thousands of factories to make way for the project.
Compensation for the resettlement amounts to 40 billion yuan (4.8
billion US dollars on May 1993 prices).
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, China has invested more than 4.5 billion yuan in
the Three Gorges resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
To better manage the fund, Qi said his bureau has will set up
five major systems in the fields of planning, account checking,
investment, statistics and auditing.
</P>
<P>
The bureau earlier imposed three rules to be observed by
government officials in the reservoir area extending from Yichang
in central China's Hubei Province to Chongqing in southwestern
Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
-- It is forbidden to use the resettlement fund for the
construction of projects not linked to the resettlement plans, the
development of real estate, or the buying of stock.
</P>
<P>
-- It is forbidden to use the resettlement fund to cover
administrative expenses, construct luxury hotels or buy cars.
</P>
<P>
-- It is forbidden to randomly adjust major resettlement
projects.
</P>
<P>
To prevent the chaotic management of the fund by various banks,
the country has also put the China Construction Bank in charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
