<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav President Expresses Condolences over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Zoran Lilic
has addressed a telegram of condolences to the family of former
Vice-President of Bosnian Serb Republic, Nikola Koljevic, who died
late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Nikola Koljevic's death is a great loss for his family,
friends and admirers," official Tanjug news agency quoted Lilic's
telegram as saying on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Nikola Koljevic will be remembered as a generous man who had
focused all his endeavors on ensuring lasting peace, freedom and
independence for his people," the telegram says.
</P>
<P>
Koljevic died at Belgrade's Military Academy Hospital late
Saturday as a result of a self-inflicted gunshot wound in the
head, according to a statement from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
Koljevic attempted suicide on January 16 in Pale, the
administrative center in Bosnia's Serb entity -- the Republika
Srpska, and was rushed to Belgrade for treatment the next day.
</P>
<P>
A brain surgery and intensive care failed to stop a
deterioration of the vital functions and he eventually died, the
hospital statement said.
</P>
<P>
Koljevic was born in Banja Luka on June 9, 1936, graduated in
world literature from Belgrade University and did post-graduate
studies in literary theory in Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
He wrote a number of books on European and Yugoslav literature,
edited literary magazines in Sarajevo and Banja Luka and taught at
Sarajevo University.
</P>
<P>
His political activity intensified at the outbreak of former
Yugoslav crisis in early 1990s and became member of the presidency
of Bosnia-Herzegovina in late 1990, a post he held until he
resigned in April 1992 when Bosnian civil war formally broke out.
</P>
<P>
He was vice president of the Republika Srpska from May 1992 to
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
