<HEADLINE> Albright: U.S. Expects Saudi Cooperation over Truck </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on Sunday said that the United States expects
Saudi Arabia to be cooperative with the investigation into last
June's truck bombing in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on NBC "Meet the Press" program, Albright said: "The
Saudis have assured us at the highest levels that they will be
cooperative, and we expect them to be cooperative."
</P>
<P>
Albright expressed her implicit criticism when she indicated
that there was no disagreement within the Clinton administration
regarding critical statements about Saudi cooperation from FBI
chief Louis Freeh and Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
Freeh and Reno on Thursday attacked the government in Riyadh
for withholding important information about the truck bombing at a
U.S. military housing complex in Dhahran, killing 19 American
servicemen.
</P>
<P>
Albright told NBC that there is a unified position within the
Clinton administration over Saudi cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We are a team, and we have a unified team," she said.
</P>
<P>
In response to the U.S. criticism, Saudi ambassador Prince
Bandar Bin Sultan said on Friday in a statement that the
conclusion of the investigation into the bombing will be made
public by Saudi authorities exclusively, indicating his government
would not provide any clues about who was behind the bombing to
anyone before any conclusion is reached.
</P>
<P>
"it would be premature to accuse or absolve anyone until the
investigation is completed," the prince said.
</P>
<P>
But Prince Bandar assured the United States that close
cooperation will continue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
