<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deputy Russian Foreign Minister Arrives in Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Russia's first Deputy Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov arrived at Belgrade on Sunday on a working
visit.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at Belgrade airport, Ivanov said current
political developments in Serbia were the country's internal
affairs and deterioration of the crisis in the Yugoslav Republic
of Serbia could complicate the situation in the country and in all
of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian opposition coalition Zajedno has staged
demonstrations over the past two months to protest the annulment
of the local elections results and demanded the recognition of
their victory in the elections on November 17, thus causing a
political crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov told reporters that the report drawn up by the
commission of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE) after its visit to Belgrade in late 1996 was
constructive, and the Yugoslav side shared this view.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE delegation report has confirmed that the Serbian
opposition coalition won local elections in 14 out of 18 major
cities across Serbia and asked the Serbian government to reinstate
the election results.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the current visit to Belgrade by a delegation
of the Russian State Duma (lower house), the deputy foreign
minister said the parliamentarians' visit, which began on
Saturday, showed that all political forces in Russia hoped that
the political situation in Yugoslavia would be normalized as soon
as possible, through political dialogue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
